{One of the most important positions to learn is those with opposite-colored
bishops. Middlegames with opposite-colored bishops (part I) A chess player,
wanting to become strong, needs to improve many different areas of their game.
This might include for example, playing positions with opposite side castling,
making positional pawn sacrifices, and playing with a knight against a bishop.
Developing experience in this or that type of position enables a player to
become better prepared and more confident when these occur in their games. It
is also important as players can then decide to enter particular types of
positions that they have studied before, for example, choosing to play with or
against the isolated queen pawn. A difficulty of such positions is that one
needs to use different rules in the middlegame and endgame. In the endgame,
the defending side should aim to build a fortress by placing pawns on the
squares of the color of their bishop. Still, the exact pawn placement may be a
critical mistake in the middlegame because the opponent can more easily
organize a potentially crushing attack using the resulting ‘holes’ in the
position. So, in choosing the correct strategy in a position with
opposite-colored bishops, one needs to answer the following questions: (1) is
my position better or worse?; and (2) how likely is the endgame to occur? The
above example is just the tip of a giant iceberg. Developing expertise in
middlegames with opposite-colored bishops can be very time-consuming. To do so
you can read different manuals about middlegame play; most will have at least
a chapter about such positions. There is also useful material on YouTube. You
can also study the games of strong GMs and study the critical moments yourself
or you can read this series of articles which the Modern Chess team provides
you with! Any material is easier to learn if it is properly structured. This
series also has a plan. In the first article, we will see examples where the
stronger bishop dominates on the long (a1-h8 / a8/ h1) diagonal. In the second
article, we will examine cases where the bishop uses the a2-g8 (a7-g1)
diagonal to dominate the position. The third article will show examples of bad
bishops in the French defense. In the final article, we will review a
collection of atypical examples and you will find some good practice pointers
for improving your middlegame play with opposite-colored bishops. So let's
begin! Positions in which one side controls the long diagonal are hazardous if
the opponent's king is in the firing line. You should be ready to sacrifice
one or even two pawns without hesitation for such an attack! We begin our
study with a game played more than 100 years ago.} 31. Bxf5 $1 {White
exchanges the only defender of the kingside and goes to attack the g7-pawn.}
exf5 32. Qg3 g6 33. Bd4 ({White missed the idea of a queen sacrifice that
might have ended the game faster} 33. Qg5 $1 Rd2 {[#] Seemingly, this is the
move that forced Perlis to play 33.Bd4.} 34. Bd4 $1 {and now} Rxg2+ 35. Qxg2
Bxg2 {leads to a checkmate (thanks to the bishop on d4).} 36. Re8+ Kh7 37. Rh8#
) 33... Qxa2 (33... Be4 {would leave some saving chances in the endgame
without an exchange.} 34. Qg5 Rxd4 35. cxd4 Qxd4) 34. Qg5 Kh7 35. Re7 {[#]} Rg8
$2 ({The only practical chance for Black was an exchange sacrifice} 35... Rxd4
$1 36. cxd4 a5 {followed by a march of a-pawn. Now the strongest continuation
is far from obvious – to support the c-pawn by Re7-d7-d6 idea.} 37. Rd7 $1 a4
38. Rd6 $1 a3 39. c6 $18 {With the bishop d4 left on the board Black has no
saving chances left.}) 36. Rd7 {White prepares the exchange of the main
defender of the Black king by means of Rd8} ({Faster way was} 36. c4 $1 {
attacking f7 and distracting the Black queen from the g2-pawn.} Qxc4 37. Qf6
$18) 36... Bd5 ({The most natural} 36... Qe6 {also would not help} 37. Rd8 Bc6
38. Rxg8 Kxg8 39. Qh6 f6 40. Qxg6+ Kf8 41. Bxf6 $18) 37. c4 $1 {Perlis used a
double distraction to free Qg5 from the defence of the g2 pawn} Qxc4 ({After} 
37... Bxc4 {the simplest win was} 38. Rd8 $1 {with inevitable mating threats.})
38. Qf6 Qa2 39. Bb2 $1 {Sufficient and the only defence of the g2-pawn} Qc4 {
Attacking f4.} 40. Qe5 {Black can't handle the Rd8 threat.} Be6 41. Rd8 $1 f6
42. Qc7+ Rg7 43. Bxf6 $1 {White ends the game with a nice tactic. Black
resigned.} 1-0

