{Thanks to a famous book by David Bronstein, Zurich-1953 is one of the most
renowned tournaments in chess history. Many of the games have become classics.
This is one of them. Now, let's look at another classical game by two renowned
GMs that was played in 1953. The dark squares around the black king are weak,
but the e5-pawn blocks the bishop on b2. To put more pressure on the
opponent's position Mark Taimanov decided to use the outpost on d6.} 23. Red1
Rd7 24. Rd6 $1 Bb7 ({The immediate capture on d6 was bad because of the
resource of Ra7} 24... Rxd6 $2 25. exd6 f6 26. Ra7 Rf7 27. Rxf7 Kxf7 28. Qxh7+
$18 {This continuation is why Yuri Averbakh first tried to defend the 7th rank.
}) 25. Rad1 ({Taimanov played the most natural move, but white had an
instructive prophylactic idea that would make a capture on d6 practically
impossible.} 25. h4 $1 Qe7 {Here white has a pleasant choice - 26.h5, 26.Rxb6
or even 26.Qg5. In all cases his advantage is clear.} ({The point of the pawn
move is that after} 25... Rxd6 $2 26. exd6 f6 27. h5 {Black can't defend all
his weaknesses:} gxh5 (27... g5 {leads to similar variations:} 28. Ra7 Rf7 29.
Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 (29... Rxf6 30. Qxg5+ Kh8 31. Rxb7 $18) 30. Qxf6 Rxf6 31. Rxb7 $18
) 28. Ra7 Rf7 29. Bxf6 $1 Qxd6 (29... Qxf6 30. Qxf6 Rxf6 31. Rxb7 $18) (29...
Rxf6 30. Qg5+ Kh8 31. Rxb7 $18) 30. Qg5+ Kf8 31. Be5 $18 {with a dream
position for White - black’s king is weak when a bishop on e5 dominates the
board.})) 25... Rxd6 26. exd6 f6 {[#]} 27. d7 $1 {White distracts Black pieces
with the offer of his passed pawn to attack his opponent's king.} ({The
immediate} 27. h4 {would not give such a positive result:} Qd7 28. h5 Qg7 {
and the worst for Black is behind him.}) 27... Bc6 28. h4 Bxd7 ({After} 28...
Rf7 {White needs to avoid the exchange of his active R by playing} 29. Rd6 $1 (
{Here is what happens if the rooks disappear from the board:} 29. h5 $2 Rxd7
30. Rxd7 Qxd7 31. hxg6 hxg6 32. Bxf6 ({or} 32. Qxg6+ Qg7 {and the mating idea
on g2 forces the exchange of queens.}) 32... Qd1+ 33. Kh2 Qh5+ $11) 29... Bxd7
{[#] One more instructive moment. White has an idea of activating his bishop.
For this, he needs to attack the pawn on f6.} 30. e4 $1 {The main idea of this
move is to play e4-e5 and after f6-f5 to bring his bishop to f6 via c1 and g5.
The second idea is to free the c1-h6 diagonal for the White queen.} Qc7 ({
An attempt to block the diagonal does not help because White will always have
the undermining ideas of f2-f4.} 30... e5 31. Qd2 Qe8 32. Qd5 Kg7 33. Rxb6 $16)
31. e5 f5 32. Bc1 $1 {White's position is close to winning.}) 29. h5 gxh5 $2 {
Äèàãðàììà [#]} ({The key for a successful Black defence was to block
the bishop on b2.} 29... g5 $1 30. f4 gxf4 $1 (30... g4 {is not so good, since
this pawn is an easy target for the White king, when Bb2 still pushes on f6.}
31. Kh2 $1 Rf7 32. Kg3 {and Bxf6 idea does not give Black time to solve all
his problems.} Qe7 ({or} 32... Qf8 33. Qxf8+ Kxf8 34. Bxf6 $16) 33. Bxf6 $1
Rxf6 34. Rxd7 Rxh6 35. Rxe7 Kf8 36. Rb7 Rxh5 37. Rxb6 Kf7 38. Kxg4 $18) 31.
exf4 ({after} 31. Qxf4 e5 {Black has got a perfect wall against Bb2.} 32. Qg3+
{and now a brave move} Kf7 $1 {holds a balance.} ({Natural} 32... Kh8 $2 {
gives White tactical motives on e5, f6 squares} 33. h6 Rf7 (33... Rg8 $2 34.
Qf3 $18 {threatening Rxd7 and Qd5.}) 34. Rd6 $1 $16 {with multiple ideas.}) 33.
Rf1 Ke6 $1 $13 {[#] This is a nice demonstration of how the defending side
should place his pawns in the middlegame with opposite-colored bishops on the
board.}) 31... Rf7 $1 32. Rd3 Qf8 $11 {and Black forces the queens exchange.
It is important to notice that Bxf6 now does not work so well because of the
f4-pawn.} 33. Qxf8+ Kxf8 34. Bxf6 Rxf6 35. Rxd7 Rxf4 36. Rxh7 Rxc4 37. Rb7 $11)
30. e4 $1 {Probably, Averbakh misevaluated this idea because all his focus had
to go on the Bb2 problem.} e5 {Black acted instinctively by trying to place
more pawns in the way of White bishop.} ({After} 30... Qe7 {White can use the
idea which we saw earlier.} 31. e5 $1 (31. Rd3 {is less convincing because of
the bishop maneuver} Be8 32. Rg3+ Bg6 {with an unclear position}) 31... f5 32.
Bc1 $1 {followed by Bg5 with strong pressure.}) 31. f4 $1 {Taimanov correctly
evaluated the importance of the long diagonal - pawns do not matter anything.}
exf4 ({The tricky way was} 31... Rf7 $1 {offering White to take on e5} 32. fxe5
({though after} 32. Qxh5 $1 exf4 33. Rd6 {White is still much better.}) 32...
fxe5 33. Bxe5 $2 {and now} Qh4 $1 $11 {The weak position of the white king
helps black to save the game.}) 32. Rd6 {Black is three pawns up, but here we
see a classical attack situation in the positions with opposite-colored
bishops and major pieces. The bishop on b2 Bb2 is much stronger than his
counterpart on d7 and all other pieces support its attacking efforts.} Qe8 33.
Bxf6 Rf7 $4 ({The only way to resist was} 33... Qg6 {giving up the exchange
and hoping to escape in the ending.} 34. Qxg6+ hxg6 35. Be7 Be8 36. Bxf8 Kxf8
37. Rxb6 Ke7 $18) 34. Rd5 $1 {Black resigned because he has no defence against
the threat of Rg5.} 1-0

