{The Soviet GM Vladimir Simagin had a sharp tactical vision and liked
positions with opposite-colored bishops. Let's see a couple of his examples. 
The starting position is uncommon. The White king is awkwardly placed on h3;
the pawn structure e5, f3, f4, g4 strengthens White's position, but the bishop
on b2 dreams about removing the pawn from e5; White’s queenside pawn
structure is terrible and all his pawns there are easy targets in the possible
endgame. The Black bishop has more reason for unhappiness with his pawns, at
the same time Ra8 feels very good and the Black king is far from a thought
about the danger. Overall, both sides have advantages and disadvantages, and
the next few moves will determine who takes the initiative. As we know, the
initiative in the middlegame with opposite-colored bishops is crucial.} 25...
dxc4 26. Qf2 c3 {26...Rxa4 would likely lead to a transposition.} 27. Bxc3 Rxa4
28. Qh4 $1 {White does not pay any attention to the f4-pawn. Simagin targets
the opponent's king.} Rxf4 $1 ({The famous Ukrainian coach Alexey Kosikov in
his excellent book "Elements of Chess Strategy" suggested the move} 28... Ra3 {
with an idea to play fxg4 after any bishop move. But this move appears a
decisive mistake and I offer you a test of your calculating skills in the
exercises section.}) 29. Qf6+ Rg7 30. Kg3 Rc4 31. Rad1 {[#] White threatens to
win the queen with Rd8 and Chistiakov automatically blocks the file.} Bd7 $2 {
[#]} ({Unfortunately for him this move blunders another bishop's maneuver.
Black had to block the c1-h6 diagonal with an intermediate check:} 31... f4+ $1
{followed by Bd7 with unclear position. For example,} 32. Kh4 Bd7 33. Rd3 (33.
Rxd7 {leads only to a perpetual check:} Qxd7 34. Rd1 Qxd1 35. Qf8+ $11) 33...
Kg8 $1 {Black should unpin the R.} 34. Rfd1 c5 $13 {The main reason why Black
holds the position is that White bishop is still passive.}) 32. Bd2 $1 {
First White threatens Bh6. In this reason Black should play} Kg8 (32... Qf7 $2
{loses after} 33. Bh6 Qxf6 34. exf6 Rf7 35. Rd3 $1 {followed by Rfd1.}) 33. Bh6
Rg6 $2 {Black blunders a nice combination that ends the game [#]} ({The
correct move again was} 33... f4+ $1 {to remove the pawn from the attack of
pawn g4. But even after this, White is winning} 34. Kg2 ({in case of} 34. Kh4
$2 Rg6 {the combination from the game already does not win because of a check.}
35. Rxd7 Rxh6+ $1 36. Qxh6 Qxd7 $14) 34... Rf7 35. Qg5+ Kh8 {and now a strong
move} 36. Qh4 $1 {followed by Bh6-g5-f6.}) 34. Rxd7 $3 {White sacrifices the
queen and gets a decisive advantage.} Rxf6 35. Rg7+ $1 Kh8 36. exf6 $18 {
The Black king is undefendable.} Qb8+ 37. f4 Rc3+ 38. Kh4 {The king feels
absolutely safe here.} Qf8 ({After} 38... fxg4 {White would need simply to
take on g4.} 39. Kxg4 $18 {with multiple threats.} (39. f7 $4 Rh3+ 40. Kxg4
Rxh6 41. Rg8+ Qxg8+ 42. fxg8=Q+ Kxg8 $19)) 39. Rxh7+ $1 Kxh7 40. Bxf8 Kg8 41.
Be7 fxg4 42. Rg1 Rh3+ 43. Kxg4 {Black resigned. The game was decided when the
White B managed to go around the e5-pawn.} 1-0

[Event "URS-ch sf"]
[Site "Gorky"]
[Date "1954.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Uusi, Gunnar"]
[Black "Simagin, Vladimir"]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "GM Valeriy Aveskulov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r3r1k1/5ppp/3qpn2/p1Nb4/3P4/R1B5/P3QPPP/2R3K1 b - - 0 22"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[EventDate "1954.??.??"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "20"]
[EventCountry "URS"]
[SourceTitle "EXT 1999"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "1998.11.10"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "1998.11.10"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

{[#] Black bishop is undoubtfully better than B on c3 and Simagin starts an
attack on the kingside.} 22... e5 ({Though, for us the main interest is to see
how this attack has worked out, we can't leave without a comment that Black
had an opportunity to crush the opponent's king's cover by a geometric tactic.
} 22... Bxg2 $1 23. Kxg2 Qd5+ 24. Kh3 (24. Kf1 $4 Qh1#) (24. Kg1 Qg5+ {and 25..
.Qxc1.}) 24... Qf5+ $1 25. Kg2 Qg5+ {and 26...Qxc1.}) 23. Qd2 e4 24. h3 {
White instinctively prevents Ng4, but the move h2-h3 weakens the dark squares.}
Nh5 $1 {N goes to f4 where it can attack on g2.} 25. Rxa5 {This pawn does not
play any role but White anyway had nothing better to play instead.} Rxa5 26.
Bxa5 Nf4 {Black wants to take on g2 followed by e4-e3+. That's why White queen
goes to block the e4-pawn.} 27. Qe3 f5 {[#]} 28. Nb7 $2 ({Uusi had seen the
Bc7 motive but has not found the correct move order.} 28. Bc7 $1 {would
minimize Black's winning chances:} Qxc7 29. Nd3 $1 Nxh3+ 30. Qxh3 Qd6 31. Ne5
$13) 28... Qh6 $1 {Black created two threats – to take on b7 and to check on
e2.} ({Of course White would be happy to exchange Nf4.} 28... Bxb7 $2 29. Bc7
$11) 29. Bd2 {[#] Another interesting tactical moment. Nf4 is attacked. How to
defend it?} ({The best practical chance was} 29. Nd6 {again offering Black to
exchange the knights. But in this case Black has one more tactical idea:} Nxh3+
$1 30. gxh3 f4 (30... Qxd6 $2 {allows to block the central pawns.} 31. Bc7 $11)
31. Qe2 ({or} 31. Qd2 e3 $19) (31. Qa3 {defends on d6 but Black already does
not need this knight.} e3 $1 32. Nxe8 Qg6+ 33. Kf1 Qg2+ 34. Ke2 Qf3+ $1 ({
White king escapes in case of} 34... Qxf2+ $4 35. Kd3 $18) 35. Kd3 (35. Ke1
Qxf2+ 36. Kd1 Bf3#) 35... exf2+ 36. Kc2 Qxa3 $19) 31... f3 32. Qe3 Qg6+ 33. Kf1
Qxd6 34. Bc7 Qe6 $19 {with a decisive attack.}) 29... g5 $2 ({Black could use
a position of the bishop on d2.} 29... Qg6 $1 30. Qxf4 e3 31. f3 exd2 32. Qxd2
Bxb7 $19 {with a free bishop.}) 30. Nc5 {A position again became unclear but
Black pieces are placed more actively.} Qg7 31. Re1 $2 {[#]} ({To defend tough
positions, one needs to find concrete threats they should handle with. Nxg2
was not a threat because of Qxg5. Seemingly, next Black's move is h7-h6 to
create a threat of capture on g2. So, White had two moves to balance the
position.} 31. Kh2 $1 {to free the queen (no fork on e2).} h6 32. Qg3 $1 {
and already Black needs to decide how to defend because White Q targets to
come on d6.}) 31... Nxg2 $1 {An easy tactic that begins a strong attack headed
by Bd5.} 32. Kxg2 f4 33. Qc3 e3+ 34. f3 $4 ({It is hard to believe but the
engine somehow resists by means of} 34. Kh2 $1 g4 35. fxe3 (35. Rg1 $2 exf2 36.
Rxg4 f1=Q $19) (35. hxg4 $4 Qh6+ 36. Kg1 Qh1#) 35... g3+ 36. Kg1 f3 {a human
simply drops the line when he sees the pawns on f3 and g3 but the engine has
no emotions.} 37. e4 $8 f2+ 38. Kg2 fxe1=Q 39. Bxe1 Bxe4+ 40. Nxe4 Rxe4 41.
Qb3+ $1 {and White has all chances to save a half the point.}) 34... g4 {
Now it is over.} 35. Rg1 Bxf3+ 36. Kf1 g3 37. Bc1 g2+ {White resigned because
of inevitable checkmate.} 0-1

