{A good illustration of bishop domination on the long diagonal occurred in the
game of the 9th World Champion. White is advantageous thanks to the much
better bishop and pressure on g7. The position can be evaluated as "close to
winning".} 33. Re3 $6 {White allowed Black to sacrifice the d5 pawn.} Rg6 $6 ({
In my opinion, d5-d4 had to be played since pawn d5 does not play any role,
while bishop b7 gets a chance.} 33... d4 $5 34. Qxd4 Kh7) 34. Bd4 $1 {Now Bb7
becomes a silent witness of the end of the game.} Kh7 35. Qc2 {The queen
attacks on f5 and prepares Rc3-c7 maneuver.} Qd7 36. Kh2 $1 {A waiting move,
that demonstrates the power of White's position, Black has nothing to do.} ({
In case of} 36. Rc3 $2 {Black would play} Rc6 {with rook exchange, which is
definitely to Black's favour - he can only dream about the ending without an
attack on his king.}) 36... Bc8 $2 {A blunder.} ({Though, after the strongest} 
36... Rc6 37. Qe2 Rc7 {his position would still be lost.} 38. g4 $1 {Brings
one more soldier to attack.}) 37. Rc3 {Rook enters on c7; the rest is easy.}
Ba6 38. Rc7 Qe6 {[#]} 39. g4 $1 Bf1 40. Qxf5 {The queen exchange does not help
Black since g7 falls down at the end.} Qxf5 41. gxf5 Rg2+ 42. Kh1 {with ideas
Rc1 and f5-f6, Black resigned.} 1-0

