[SourceQuality "1"]

{Now we have some instructive examples from more recent times. In 2002 Garry
Kasparov was still an active player. In the next game, he crushed his opponent
with the activity of his dark-squared bishop.  In the position on the diagram,
both long diagonals are under the control of the opponents' bishops. At the
moment, none of the sides can create severe threats to the opponent's king.
But both should be careful of such possibilities.} 33... Nxd3 $2 {The Spanish
GM had to foresee that this capture would help White rook to appear on g3, but
seemingly he had some miscalculation.} ({The correct} 33... bxc4 34. Bxc4 Nd5 {
would keep the balance, since} 35. Qe5 {does not checkmate} Qg6) 34. Rxd3 {
Instantly, Black's position became terrible. Nothing can help against Rg3. The
attack in the middlegame with opposite-colored bishops again proves its own
extraordinary.} Nf7 ({After} 34... bxc4 {White does not even need to take the
pawn.} 35. Rg3 $1 Rb3 {[#] A good try to exchange the attacking piece (Rg3).
How would you play here?} 36. Rcc3 $1 ({An alternative way to avoid the
exchange of Rg3 was not the same good since Black can sacrifice an exchange
and save the c4-pawn.} 36. Bc3 $2 Rxc3 $1 37. Rcxc3 Bd5 {with unclear play.})
36... Qg6 ({Engine offers to give up the exchange right now (before it became
too late).} 36... Rxb2 $5 37. Qxb2 {But if we compare this position to one
that arose in line 34...bxc4 35. Rg3 Rb3 36.Bc3 Rxc3 Black has no time to
defend on c4.} Qb8 $1 38. Qxb8 Rxb8 39. Rxc4 {and White should finally win.})
37. Rxb3 cxb3 38. Nxe6 Ng4+ 39. hxg4 Qh6+ 40. Kg1 Qxe6 41. Qxe6+ dxe6 42. gxf5
$18 {and Rxg7}) 35. Rg3 Nxg5 36. Rxg5 Rf7 37. Qe5 Qf8 38. cxb5 $18 {[#] White
won the pawn and saved the attacking position. The result is determined. The
next moves do not present any special interest for us. Garry Kasparov was
increasing the pressure and finally, the Spanish GM blundered the tactical
blow that you can find in the exercises section.} *

[Event "Aeroflot Open A 2016"]
[Site "Moscow RUS"]
[Date "2016.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Pichot, A.."]
[Black "Khismatullin, D.."]
[Result "0-1"]
[Annotator "GM Valeriy Aveskulov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1qr1r1k1/3n1pp1/3Q4/4p1Bp/4b2P/1P4P1/2P1NP2/2RR2K1 b - - 0 22"]
[PlyCount "19"]
[EventDate "2016.03.01"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]
[SourceTitle "The Week in Chess 1113"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]
[SourceDate "2016.03.07"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2016.03.07"]
[SourceQuality "2"]

{The Russian GM Denis Khismatullin has an interesting and active style.
Let’s see how he took control of the weak diagonal in the game against the
Argentine GM Alan Pichot. The position of the White king is not safe but White
has a free pawn and Black pieces are very passive. The only compensating
factor is the presence of opposite-colored bishops on the board, which is more
than enough for a pawn. All Black needs to do is  save the queens on the board;
that's why the next move is required  (if Black aims to win).} 22... Rc7 $1 23.
Nc3 {Black wanted to pin the knight by a move Bf3.} ({An alternative move
might be} 23. Kh2 {which is a typical defending setup in similar situations
– K goes to h2 (h7) and R defends on g2 from g1. This disables a Q's mate on
these squares. But here it would leave Ne2 in the problematic situation.} Nf8
$1) 23... Rxc3 24. Qxd7 ({White has no option to exchange the queen before
taking the knight because of} 24. Qxb8 $4 Nxb8) 24... Rec8 $6 {An inaccuracy
that gave White a chance to exchange some pieces.} (24... f6 {was the better
move since it pushes the B away from the d8-square.}) 25. Qd6 $2 {White
targets the exchange of the queens, but Black easily copes with this.} ({
The correct idea was not so natural} 25. Qe7 $1 {followed by Rd8.} Rxc2 26.
Rxc2 Bxc2 27. Rd8+ Rxd8 28. Qxd8+ Qxd8 29. Bxd8 Bxb3 $11 {a free pawn does not
matter; White easily makes a draw in such endgame.}) 25... Qb5 $1 {Surely,
Black avoids this exchange.} 26. Re1 Ba8 $1 {[#] Black's intention is obvious
– Qb7. All White can do is to give up an exchange.} 27. Ra1 $8 Qb7 28. Rxa8
$8 Qxa8 29. Qxe5 Rxc2 $17 {White has some saving chances, but the Argentian
player shortly blundered a tactic orientated on the weakness of the long
diagonal.} 30. Be3 $2 ({The endgame R vs B with 3 vs 3 pawns is more or less
easily winning, but if we add one more pair of the rooks, the win is already
more problematic. That's why it might make sense to fight for the long
diagonal by a move} 30. Qe4) 30... Re8 31. Qxh5 $4 {Any other normal retreat
was better.} Rxe3 $1 {Looking at this game, we can see that Bg5 was a silent
spectator of what was happening on the board.} 0-1

[Event "9th European Individual Ch (m)"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2008.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Aveskulov, V.."]
[Black "Lubczynski, Rafal"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "GM Valeriy Aveskulov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "2br2k1/1p4p1/r4p1p/p1pPp2q/P1P1Q3/1R6/1BP2PPP/R5K1 w - - 0 24"]
[PlyCount "24"]
[EventDate "2008.04.21"]
[EventRounds "11"]
[EventCountry "BUL"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]

{The next game is further proof of the rule that "in middlegames with
opposite-colored bishops, the initiative can often be more important than a
pawn". For me, it was clear, that f2-f4 is the correct plan in this position.
White needs to free the diagonal for his bishop.} 24. Qe3 $6 {A mistake. I
chose to play f2-f4 immediately or first to attack c5. I thought it was more
practical to force Black to play b7-b6 and make Ra6 passive. But an unblocking
of the e5-pawn and the freeing of Bc8 were more important factors in the
position. I had to be more concrete in my calculating.} ({An immediate} 24. f4
$1 {was stronger since Black can not avoid the opening of the f-file.} Bf5 {
Looks the most natural – Black aims to take on c2 but that pawn does not
play any role.} ({White easily attacks Black's weaknesses in the endgame after
} 24... Qf5 $2 25. Qxf5 Bxf5 26. fxe5 fxe5 27. Rxb7 Bxc2 28. Bxe5 Rg6 29. Rb5
$18) 25. Qe3 exf4 26. Qxf4 {Black should defend on b7.} Rd7 27. Re1 $1 {
with an attack. A capture on c2 instantly loses the game.} Bxc2 $2 28. Rh3 Qg5
29. Qb8+ Kh7 30. Re8 $18) 24... b6 25. f4 {[#]} exf4 $2 ({Luckily for me, my
opponent didn't realize that a pawn sacrifice} 25... e4 $1 {allowed him to
place own pieces harmoniously.} 26. h3 $1 ({A capture on e4 opens both e-file
and b1-h7 diagonal for Black rook and bishop:} 26. Qxe4 $2 Re8 27. Qd3 Bf5 28.
Qg3 Kf8 {and the difference between bishops is to Black's favour now.}) 26...
Qg6 {followed by h6-h5, Bf5. Position is still better for White but Black
manages to get a nice position on the king side.}) 26. Qxf4 {[#]} Qf5 $2 ({
Another critical position. The control over the e-file is a goal for both
sides. But a direct} 26... Re8 $2 {is bad due to} 27. Rg3 $1 {with a strong
attack:} ({A reflexory} 27. Bxf6 $2 {helps Black to exchange the queens and to
secure own king.} Qf5 $1 (27... gxf6 $4 28. Rg3+ Kf7 29. Qc7+ Re7 30. Qxc8 $18)
28. Qxf5 Bxf5 29. Rg3 Ra7 {White pawns on the queen side are badly placed for
the endgame.}) 27... Rf8 (27... Kh7 $4 28. Rxg7+ $1 {with a checkmate.}) 28.
Qd6 $1 $16 {with ideas Bxf6 or Re1-e7.}) ({The correct way was again connected
with a pawn sacrifice:} 26... Ra7 $1 27. Rg3 ({after} 27. Rxb6 Re8 {followed
by Rae7 Black has a decent compensation.}) 27... Kh7 28. Re1 Re8 {and no
tactic on f6, g7 squares works.}) 27. Qe3 $6 {White primitively prevents Re8
and prepares Qe7. Other retreats were more dangerous for Black.} (27. Qd2 {
with ideas Rf1 and Rg3.}) (27. Qg3 $40) ({or} 27. Qc7 $5 {with an idea first
to force the Black queen to go to a passive position.} Qd7 28. Qg3 $40) 27...
Bd7 $2 {Allows White to destroy the Black king's cover.} ({Surely, Black was
not going to take on c2:} 27... Qxc2 $2 {This position can be found in the
exercises section.}) ({Instead Black could play} 27... Rf8 $1 {defending on f6
and attacking on c2. White has nothing but to admit the mistake of the
previous move by playing 28.Qd2 or 28.Qe2.}) 28. Rf1 Qxc2 {[#]} 29. Bxf6 $1 {
White finds an easy tactic and it might have been the end of the story. But I
have made at least one more mistake that is instructive.} Rf8 (29... gxf6 $2
30. Qe7 $1 {leads to a forcing mate.}) 30. Qg3 ({After} 30. Bxg7 $2 Rxf1+ 31.
Kxf1 {[#] Black has an impressive move} b5 $1 {that again proves the principle
"pawns matter not so much in the middlegames with opposite-colored bishops".
Connecting Ra6 to the kingside is more important.} ({Honestly speaking, White
has no win even after} 31... Kxg7 32. Qe7+ Kg6 $1 33. Rg3+ Kh5 $1 34. Qf7+ Kh4
$11 {but this king's walk does not look so safe without engine's assistance.}))
30... Rf7 31. Rbf3 Bxa4 {My weak play begins from now. First, I didn't find
the best retreat square for the bishop.} 32. Be5 (32. Ba1 $1 {enabling Qb8-Rf8
play was stronger.} Rb7 (32... Rd7 33. Rf8+ Kh7 34. Qb8 $18) 33. Rf8+ Kh7 34.
Qg4 $1 $18 {with ideas Qc8 or Qe6.}) 32... Rd7 ({White takes almost all pawns
with checks after} 32... Raa7 33. Rxf7 Rxf7 34. Rxf7 Kxf7 35. Qxg7+ Ke8 36.
Qg8+ Kd7 37. Qe6+ Kd8 38. Qxb6+ Kd7 39. Qc7+ Ke8 40. Qc8+ Kf7 (40... Ke7 41.
Qxc5+) 41. Qe6+ Kf8 42. Qxh6+ $18) 33. Qg4 ({Here White also could use Ba1-Qb8
idea:} 33. Rf8+ Kh7 34. Ba1 $1 Rb7 35. Qg4 $18 {(threatening Qc8 or Qe6)})
33... Ra8 34. Qe6+ Kh7 {Black prepares Qg6 and White plays} 35. h3 $2 {This
mistake might have over crossed all previous achievements. Luckily, White
still had a winning combination.} ({The prophylactical thinking is required at
all stages of the chess game, even when one is attacking. To win convincingly,
White had to play} 35. Rg3 $1 {preventing Qg6. Black is helpless against
White's attack. First, Qxd7 threatens.} Raa7 36. d6 $1 {Another prophylactical
move; this time White stops Re7.} Qe4 37. h3 $1 $18 {making a luft for the
king and preparing Rf8. It's over.}) 35... Qg6 $1 {This position can be found
in the exercises section.} *

[Event "14th Karpov GM"]
[Site "Poikovsky RUS"]
[Date "2013.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Sutovsky, E.."]
[Black "Onischuk, Al"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "GM Valeriy Aveskulov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "2r2rk1/2p1q1pp/p3b3/1p6/4R3/6Q1/PP3PPP/R1B3K1 b - - 0 21"]
[PlyCount "42"]
[EventDate "2013.08.28"]
[EventType "tourn"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "RUS"]
[EventCategory "18"]
[SourceTitle "The Week in Chess 983"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]
[SourceDate "2013.09.09"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "2013.09.09"]
[SourceQuality "2"]

{[#] The position on the diagram can be evaluated as equal since none of the
sides has the initiative. But considering an absence of a pawn on f7 Black has
to be more cautious to White's idea to bring the bishop to the long diagonal.
How would you fight against this idea?} 21... Qf7 $6 {Alexander Onischuk
failed to find a correct move and allowed the White bishop to reach so
desirable diagonal without any resistance.} (21... Qd7 $1 {preventing Bd2 was
a better try. Moreover, after} 22. Bf4 {Black could begin the pressure on g2
by means of} Rf6 $5 $13) 22. Bd2 $1 Bf5 ({Of course, Black did not want to
help White rook by means of} 22... Bd5 23. Rg4 Qd7 24. Bc3 Rf7 25. Rd1 c6 26.
Rd3 {with an idea to double rooks on the g-file (for example, after h2-h3, Qh4)
. White has an obvious initiative.}) 23. Re5 {Temporary the rook blocks the
diagonal.} c5 24. Rae1 Rfe8 {[#]} 25. h4 $1 {A good practical decision - White
does not force things. Instead, Sutovsky creates an idea to weaken the dark
squares even more by h4-h5-h6 and makes a luft for his king.} Bg6 26. a3 $1 {
Another master move - the Israel GM prepares a place for the bishop on c3.
Black does not have simplifying ideas and White's initiative quickly grows up.}
Qd7 27. Bc3 Rxe5 28. Rxe5 b4 {Practically the only reasonable defense - Black
tries to distract White pieces from his own king's residence. Otherwise, White
would play h4-h5 and then h5-h6 or Rg5.} 29. axb4 cxb4 30. Bxb4 Qd3 {[#] Black
created a double threat to enter the endgame without a pawn or to take on b2.
How should White play?} 31. Re3 $1 {White correctly evaluates that it is
better to give a pawn back but to leave the queens on the board.} Qb1+ 32. Kh2
Qxb2 33. Qg4 $2 {White missed a nice geometric idea but Black left this unused.
} ({White had a stronger alternative –} 33. Bc3 $1 Qb7 34. Qg5 {with an idea
of h4-h5.} Re8 35. Rg3 $1 {White again should escape the exchange.} Qe7 {[#]}
36. h5 $1 {Now even the exchange does not help Black.} Qxg5 37. Rxg5 Bd3 38.
Rxg7+ Kf8 39. Rd7 $18 {Black avoided the quick loss and managed to trade off
the queen but this endgame should be lost.}) 33... Rd8 $2 ({Black missed his
chance.} 33... Qc2 $1 {A first impression that after} 34. h5 {Black still
should be lost, but} Qf5 $1 {forces the queen exchange and position to become
equal. The c2-c8-f5 triangle looks nice.}) 34. Bc3 Qb8+ 35. Rg3 $18 {White has
improved all his pieces and is ready for the final attack. An absence of the
pawns on the queenside does not matter.} Rd5 ({Interesting variations come
after} 35... Qc8 36. Qg5 Rf8 $1 {The best try.} 37. Qd5+ $1 (37. h5 $2 {
is bad due to} Rf5) ({when an immediate} 37. Qe5 {does not give a required
result quickly:} Qd7 38. h5 Rf5 39. Qb8+ Qe8 40. Qxe8+ Bxe8 41. Rxg7+ Kf8 {
and pawn h5 can not be defended well. Though, here I would like to show you a
bit more.} 42. Rxh7 Bxh5 $8 $16 {it is hard to say if White is winning or not,
but he has good chances here.} ({After} 42... Rxh5+ $2 43. Rxh5 Bxh5 {Black is
surprisingly losing after} 44. Kh3 {[#] First I was convinced that Black
easily makes a draw here. But a deeper look helped to see that Black does not
have time to prevent an appearance of the White king on g5 (because of the
worst possible position of own bishop). After that nothing can stop the idea
of placing White pawns on the 5th rank. Let me remind you that the defending
idea in such endgames sounds as follows: when two pawns stay together (for
example d5 and e5) the defending king and bishop should be placed like Kd7 and
Bf7 (g8), preventing e5-e6 and attacking on d5 (this is needed to prevent the
king's maneuvers). The problem of this concrete position is that with pawns on
f5 and g5 Black bishop will not have enough space to control g5-g6 and to
attack f5 (for this purpose, only the h7-square is good, but with the king on
f7 and the bishop on h7 Black will be in a zugzwang). It means that Black
should do the analogic plan when White pawns on the 4th rank (King on g6 and
bishop on e6 (d7, c8). That's why it is so important for White to place his
king on g5 and to prevent an appearance of the Black king on g6.} Kf7 (44...
Be8 45. Kh4 Kf7 46. Kg5 $18) 45. Kh4 Bd1 (45... Kg6 46. g4 $18 {this is why I
called the h5-square the worst possible for the bishop.}) 46. Kg5 Bc2 47. f4
Be4 48. g4 Bc2 49. f5 Bd3 50. Kf4 Bc2 51. g5 $18)) 37... Kh8 (37... Rf7 38. h5
$18) 38. Qe5 $1 {Now the same defence is not helping Black.} Qd7 39. h5 Rf5 40.
Qb8+ Qe8 41. Qxe8+ Bxe8 42. Rxg7 $18 {a discovered check will end the game.})
36. Qe6+ Bf7 37. Qe7 Qf4 (37... Qd6 38. Qxd6 Rxd6 39. Rxg7+ Kf8 40. Rxh7 $18 {
and three pawns should easily win the game.}) 38. Bb4 ({Seemingly, Sutovsky
knew that White was winning after} 38. Bxg7 Qxg3+ 39. Kxg3 Kxg7 40. Kf4 {
and decided to set a trap before going to this endgame. It has worked out well.
}) 38... Bg6 $2 {[#] Black blunders!} ({After the strongest} 38... Qb8 {
White would be "forced" to win the queen with} 39. Bc3 Qf4 40. Bxg7 $18) 39.
Qe6+ Qf7 40. Rf3 $3 {Black resigned, material loses are inevitable.} Bf5 ({
After} 40... Qxe6 {he gets mated by} 41. Rf8#) (40... Rf5 {also does not help}
41. Qc8+ Qe8 42. Qxe8+ Bxe8 43. Rxf5 $18) 41. Rxf5 $1 Rxf5 42. Qc8+ $18 {
I a@m to share my knowledge with the chess community in writing these articles.
I love to see the impact of my work. So if my article has inspired you to play
a promising attack with opposite-colored bishops, please feel free to email me
at vdaveskulovîgmail.com and I may include your game in a future article.} 1-0

