{[#] On the previous move (h2-h3) White allowed his opponent to trap his Q for
the exchange, but luckily there still was a winning combination.} 36. Rf6 $1 (
36. Rg3 {leads to the position where Black can build a fortress.} Qxe6 37. dxe6
Re7 38. Rf7 Rxf7 39. exf7 g5 40. Rf3 Rf8 41. Bd6 Kg7 42. Bxf8+ Kxf8 {[#] I can
be wrong but I found the only winning line for White.} 43. Rf6 $1 (43. Kf2 $2
b5 44. cxb5 Bxb5 45. Rf5 Bc4 {followed by Bxf7 leads to a fortress (for
example, you can find in a database the game Kostic-Perunovic, SCG-chT, 2004).}
) 43... Bb3 44. Rxh6 a4 45. Rxb6 Bxc4 46. Rg6 $1 {White need to take on g5.} (
46. Rc6 $2 a3 47. Rxc5 a2 48. Ra5 g4 $1 49. hxg4 ({or} 49. h4 g3 $1 $11 {
and the White king is stalemated.}) 49... Kxf7 {is drawn}) 46... a3 47. Rxg5 a2
48. Rg8+ Kxf7 49. Ra8 $18 {This means that in the exercise position, White had
two winning ways. But this one looks way harder.}) 36... gxf6 37. Rxf6 Re8 $1 {
It is a move to foresee when one is going to play 36.Rf6.} (37... Qg7 38. Qf5+
{and Rg6+-}) 38. Qxb6 $1 {At first sight, it looks so that White Q from b6
does not create threats to the Black king. But there is a b1-h7 diagonal.} Qxf6
(38... Qh5 39. Qb1+ $1 {The key move.} Kg8 40. Rg6+ Kf8 (40... Kf7 41. Rg7+ Kf8
42. Qh7 $18) 41. Qf1+ Rf7 42. Bd6+ Ree7 43. Bxe7+ {[#]} Ke8 $1 {A nice defence,
that forces White to find a few more precise moves.} ({or} 43... Kxe7 44. Qe1+
$1 {and Black K has no good squares:} Kf8 (44... Kd8 45. Qxa5+) (44... Kd7 45.
Qe6+) 45. Qg3 $1 $18) 44. Rg8+ Kd7 45. Qe1 $1 Rxe7 46. Qxa5 Re1+ 47. Qxe1 $18)
39. Qxf6 $18 {White is winning since there is still an attack with opposite
colored bishops.} *

