{Middlegames with opposite-colored bishops (part II) This is the second
article from a series dedicated to the study of middlegames with
opposite-colored bishops. We will review examples in which one of the sides
had pressure on the f7 (f2) square thanks to a much better bishop. We start
with simpler cases, where the bishop's domination is obvious before covering
examples where securing the dominant bishop requires some preparation with a
pawn sacrifice. To finish, we will examine a few instructive mistakes in which
the losing side in underestimating the bishop’s power enabled their opponent
to obtain a decisive advantage. SIMPLER CASES Let's start with a simple
example. The difference between the bishops is obvious and it predetermines
the White's advantage. All White pieces are concentrated on the f7-pawn and
Black is absolutely stalemated. So, White pushes the g-pawn to get the
quantitive advantage in attack.} 33. Kg2 Qd7 34. g4 $1 Qe8 35. g5 {g5-g6 is a
threat and Black can't defend on f7 anymore.} Qd7 36. gxh6 gxh6 (36... g6 37.
Qxg6+) 37. Qg6+ Kh8 (37... Bg7 38. Rg3 $18) 38. Bxf7 Bg7 39. Bd5 {Pawn is won,
but the attack has not ended yet.} Qd8 40. Rc3 {The idea is Be6 and Rc8.} Re8
41. Rc7 Re7 (41... Qxc7 42. Qxe8+ Kh7 43. Bg8+ Kh8 44. Bf7+ Kh7 45. Bg6#) 42.
Rc6 Bf6 43. Bf7 (43. Qxf6+ $4 Rg7+ {loses a queen}) {Black resigned because
after} 43... Bg7 44. Be6 {there was no a defense against Rc8 or Bf5 threats.}
1-0

[Event "CHN-chT 6th"]
[Site "China"]
