[Source "Mark Crowther"]

{[#] Older engines evaluated this position as +/- but Stockfish 14 is more
confident and gives about +2.5 for White. Nevertheless, the following Black's
move is a huge strategic mistake.} 16... b4 $2 (16... Rc8 17. g4 f6 {was the
better way to defend.}) 17. Nd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 a5 {There are no chances to get
a severe attack on the queenside. A more critical factor is a loss of control
over the c4-square. From there White bishop will strongly support the kingside
attack.} 19. g4 {White simply pushes his pawns forward.} Qc7 ({Surely, the
pawn on h4 can not be taken for free:} 19... Bxh4 $2 20. Qh3 $18) 20. g5 a4 21.
Bc4 Ra5 $2 {Simplifies the White's attack.} ({Black had to try} 21... Kh8 {
with an idea of f7-f6. Of course, it also does not save the game, but White
would have at least some difficulties with a choice.} 22. h5 ({after} 22. f6 {
Black already can take the pawn.} gxf6 23. gxf6 ({instead} 23. Rd2 $1 {gives
White has a strong initiative; fxg5 is never good due to the opening of the
h-file.}) 23... Bxf6 {with practical chances to survive.}) 22... f6 23. g6 h6
24. Rc1 $18 {Black's position is so terrible that even the endgame with only
bishops left on the board will be lost for him (White will easily organize a
passed pawn on the queenside).}) 22. f6 $1 {The following lines are easy and
do not require comments.} Bd8 (22... gxf6 $2 23. gxf6 Bxf6 24. Rg1+ Kh8 25. Qh6
Qd8 26. Rxa5 $18) 23. h5 Rxd5 24. Bxd5 axb3 25. Bxb3 Qb6 26. Qf3 {g5-g6 is a
threat.} Kh8 27. fxg7+ Kxg7 28. g6 $1 Bg5 (28... fxg6 $4 29. h6+ Kh8 30. Qxf8#)
29. gxf7 Qe3 30. Qxe3 Bxe3 31. Kc2 {The f7-pawn and a pawn majority on the
queenside guarantee White an easy win.} h6 32. Bd5 Rb8 33. Rh3 Bf4 34. a4 bxa3
35. bxa3 Kf8 36. a4 Rc8+ 37. Rc3 {Black resigned.} 1-0

