[SourceQuality "1"]

{[#] There is a typical Sicilian position. Normally, in the positions with
e7-e5, Black should not allow the White bishop to reach the a2-g8 diagonal 
(for this purpose, he can play Be6, b7-b5 or Qc7). In this game, Black failed
to handle this, and White got a serious advantage. Square d5 is weak, the
a2-g8 diagonal is under his total control. Timofeev decided to increase his
own presence on the d5-square by playing} 17. Nf1 $1 Rab8 {Black prepares
b6-b5, using the fact that Qxa6 leaves the e4-pawn without a defense.} 18. Ng3
$1 {Surprisingly White N changed his path. Black should defend on a6.} b5 19.
axb5 axb5 {[#]} 20. Nh5 $1 {An idea of this exchange is connected with the
hole on d5.} b4 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Nd5 Bxd5 23. Rxd5 $16 {[#] The goal is
achieved. The position is better for White since Bb3 is perfectly placed  
(controls d5, attacks on f7, and safety defend on c2).} Ra8 24. Rad1 {Surely,
White avoids exchanges since White rooks have much more to do.} Be7 25. Qh5 Bf8
26. R5d3 $1 {The rook moves to f3. Black's position is hopeless.} Ra7 ({After} 
26... Rd8 27. Rg3 Kh8 {White could even take with a queen} 28. Qxf7 $18) 27.
Rf3 Rca8 28. g3 Qe7 29. Rxf7 Qxf7 30. Bxf7+ Rxf7 31. Qe2 $18 {The end of the
game does not present any interest; White convincingly won.} *

[Event "42-nd Olympiad Baku"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2016.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nepomniachtchi, Ian"]
[Black "Hracek, Zbynek"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Annotator "GM Valeriy Aveskulov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "r4rk1/5ppp/3p1b2/4p3/pqP1P2P/3Q2PB/RP3P2/5K1R w - - 0 22"]
[PlyCount "39"]
[EventDate "2016.??.??"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]
[WhiteClock "1:15:24"]
[BlackClock "0:30:34"]

{[#] In the position White bishop hardly could impress someone. But already
next Nepo's move began to change things.} 22. Bd7 $1 {White's idea is obvious
- he directs his B to d5. Considering that both a4 and d6 pawns are under
attack, it appears impossible to prevent it. That's why Hracek decided to do
the same – to improve his bishop.} Bd8 ({It is worth mentioning that Black
had an interesting active alternative.} 22... Qb3 23. Qxb3 axb3 24. Ra3 $1 {
White targets to win on b3, but Black has what to answer.} Rxa3 25. bxa3 {[#]}
d5 $1 {A typical sacrifice for the endgames with the opposite-colored bishops.
Black opens up the diagonals for his bishop.} 26. exd5 (26. cxd5 Rb8 27. Ke2
Be7 28. a4 b2 29. Rb1 Bc5 $44 {followed by Bd4.}) 26... Rd8 $1 ({after} 26...
e4 $6 {White advances the c-pawn to the 6th rank.} 27. c5) 27. Bc6 e4 28. Ke2
Bd4 $1 29. Rd1 b2 $44) 23. Bc6 Ra7 24. Qc2 {[#] White attacked on a4, and
Black decided to defend it.} a3 $2 {Czech GM definitely knew that the activity
of the bishop means more than a pawn in the positions with the
opposite-colored bishops. But one thing to know the rule, another thing is to
be able to apply it in practice.} ({A correct decision was} 24... Bb6 $1 {
ignoring the a4-pawn.} 25. Rxa4 ({or} 25. Bxa4 Bd4 {with an obvious and
sufficient compensation.}) 25... Rxa4 26. Bxa4 Bd4 27. b3 Qb7 $1 {(preventing
Bc6 and preparing f7-f5). The situation on the board has changed significantly
- the black bishop is a hero when its counterpart looks miserable on a4; f7-f5
will open the f-file to get pressure on f2. Now White is a side that should
defend carefully.}) 25. Kg2 $1 {Evidently, Black missed this idea. White
prepares Rb1 that will give him control over the b-file followed by entering
on b7. Hard to believe but the Black's position is practically lost.} Qc5 (
25... Bb6 $1 {again the activization of the bishop was a strong decision (at
least from the practical point of view). After} 26. Rb1 Bd4 27. bxa3 Qc5 {
Black even takes on a3 back.} 28. Bd5 Rxa3 29. Rxa3 Qxa3 30. Rb7 {followed by
Qe2-f3 (or h5) with a super pressure on f7. But a presence of the bishop on d4
makes this not so hopeless.}) 26. Bd5 g6 27. Rb1 axb2 28. Raxb2 {[#]
Strategically, it is over for Black. Bishops are too different.} Kh8 29. Rb5
Qc8 ({After} 29... Qd4 $2 {Black does not lose the queen but puts the latter
too far away from the weakness on d6:} 30. Rd1 Ra2 $8 31. Qxa2 Qxd1 32. Qa3 $1
Bc7 (32... Be7 33. Rb7 $18) 33. Rb7 Bb8 34. Rxb8 $1 Rxb8 35. Qxd6 $18) 30. Rb8
Qd7 31. Qd2 {Looking at the h6-square.} Kg7 32. R8b7 Rxb7 33. Rxb7 Qg4 ({Or} 
33... Bc7 34. h5 $18) 34. Qa2 $1 {Nepo ignored the h4-pawn and directed his
queen to attack on f7.} Bxh4 35. Qa7 Kh6 36. Rxf7 Rxf7 37. Qxf7 {Black loses
on d6.} Bg5 38. Qf8+ Kh5 39. Qxd6 {A march of the c-pawn will decide the game.}
Bf4 40. Qf6 Qg5 41. Qf7 {Black resigned.} 1-0

[Event "SWE-URS"]
[Site "Stockholm"]
