{[#] White has active pieces on the kingside but his queenside is less
harmonious. Kasparov decided to sacrifice the pawn in order to grab control
over the a2-g8 diagonal.} 25. c4 $1 bxc4 26. bxc4 Bxc4 $2 ({There was no need
to follow the opponent's plan. Black could attack the bishop to see where it
goes.} 26... h6 $1 27. Bxf6 ({There is not much compensation for the pawn after
} 27. Be3 $6 Bxc4 28. Nxc4 Qxc4 29. Bb3 Qb4 $15) ({There is nothing to do on
h4:} 27. Bh4 g6 28. Ne3 Kg7 {with an idea of Nc5. Black pieces are more
harmoniously placed.}) 27... Nxf6 28. Ne3 ({White does not have time to bring
the R closer to the king.} 28. Re3 $2 g6 29. Rg3 Nxe4 $17) 28... g6 $15 {
followed by h6-h5, Rc8, Bh6. White bishop remains bad and Black has no
problems.}) 27. Nxc4 Qxc4 28. Bb3 Qc3 {[#]} 29. Kh2 $1 {A quiet move that
brings the king away from possible checks on the first rank and underlines
Black's difficulties. Almost all of his subsequent moves promise to be
difficult.} h6 30. Bxf6 {White does not need this bishop.} Nxf6 31. Re3 $1 Qc7
32. Rf3 {White puts pressure on the f6, f7 squares. A concrete threat is Nxh6.}
Kh7 $2 ({The modern engine shows that Black needed to regroup his major pieces
in order to defend these squares better.} 32... Qd8 $1 33. Ne3 Ra7 $1) 33. Ne3
{White threatens to play Nd5 to win on f7.} Qe7 $2 {[#] I guess that already
at this moment Karpov had seen the fortress idea.} ({Engines are even more
brave and ready to give up on f7 for free!} 33... Be7 $1 34. Bxf7 Rf8 35. Be6
g6 {followed by h6-h5 with a solid position.}) 34. Nd5 Nxd5 35. Bxd5 Ra7 36.
Qb3 ({Kasparov increases pressure instead of a win of the queen.} 36. Rxf7 Qxf7
37. Bxf7 Rxf7 $14 {The point is that after inevitable g7-g5 Black would build
an inaccessible fortress – K can be on g7, B on e7, f8 squares and R can
move on f7 and f6. Even if the White king arrives on d5, it is not clear what
to do next.}) 36... f6 $2 ({Alexey Kosikov in his "Elements of Chess Strategy"
correctly offered} 36... Kg8 $1 37. Qb8 $1 {with a tricky idea to take on f7
and then to take on a7.} ({I do not see how the extra queen can help White
after} 37. Rxf7 Qxf7 38. Bxf7+ Rxf7 39. Qe6 ({or} 39. h4 g6) 39... g5 $1 40.
Qg6+ Bg7 41. Qxd6 Rxf2 $11) 37... Qc7 $1 (37... g6 $4 38. Rxf7 Qxf7 39. Qxa7
$18) 38. Rxf7 Qxb8 39. Rb7+ Kh7 40. Rxb8 Be7 $11 {and then g7-g6, h6-h5; this
endgame should be drawn.}) 37. Qb8 {The Black's position became critical.
White aims to bring his rook to c8.} g6 {[#]} 38. Rc3 $2 {An inaccuracy that
allowed Black to survive.} ({The correct move was} 38. g4 $1 {that makes h6-h5
more difficult to advance. Having the pawn on h6 Black king has severe space
problems. For example,} Rd7 ({after} 38... Rc7 39. Ra3 {Black can't hold the
8-th rank.}) 39. Rc3 Rd8 40. Qb6 f5 $1 {Practically the only chance.} ({
Black can't stand on the place:} 40... Kg7 41. Rc7 Rd7 42. Rc8 Kh7 43. Qb8 Kg7
44. Re8 $18) 41. exf5 gxf5 42. Be6 $1 $16 {and White continues to attack.})
38... h5 $1 39. g4 ({After} 39. Rc8 Bg7 {White has no a checkmate} 40. Rh8+
Bxh8 41. Qg8+ {because of free h6-square.} Kh6 42. Qxh8+ Qh7 43. Qxf6 Qg7 {
and Black is fine.}) 39... Kh6 $1 {Karpov again made the only move. Black does
not want to open the g-file.} 40. gxh5 ({An alternative way was} 40. Qb6 $5 {
not determining the situation on the kingside.}) 40... Kxh5 $1 41. Rc8 $2 ({
Position would remain tough for Black in case of} 41. Qc8 $5 {The engine holds
the position by means of} f5 $1 ({After the natural human's move} 41... Kh6 $2
42. Rg3 Rc7 43. Qg4 Qe8 44. Qh4+ Kg7 45. Qh5 Re7 (45... Ra7 46. Be6 $1 {
and Bf5.}) 46. h4 {White has a desicive attack.}) 42. exf5 Qf6 $1 $13 {giving
White no easy attack.}) 41... Bg7 {The position became equal and the opponents
agreed for a draw.} 1/2-1/2

