{[#] Black threatens to take on d2 and c3. Most of the players would play 27.
Bc1 that is a good move. But Adams has recognized patterns of the good
position with opposite-colored bishops on the board and dared to sacrifice the
pawn to reach a dream.} 27. Bb3 $5 ({After} 27. Bc1 {Black can't force a draw
by a repetition} Nb6 28. Ra3 Nc4 {because White can play} 29. Ra6 {preventing
Nc4-b6 move. But in the position after 27.Rc1 Stockfish 14 showed a fantastic
move 27...d5!! All previous versions of Stockfish didn't show this. I offer
you to learn that position yourself. You will definitely be impressed.}) 27...
Nxd2 $6 ({The Russian GM missed a strong pawn's sacrifice to free his  bishop.
} 27... d5 $1 {that opens Bf8 to attack on b4 and closes the a2-g8 diagonal. A
true master decision from the engine!} 28. Bxc4 {The best answer. Other moves
lead to worse positions.} (28. Qxd5 $4 Rd8 $19 {loses Bd2.}) (28. exd5 Nxd2 29.
Qxd2 Rxc3 $15) (28. Ra2 Nxd2 29. Qxd2 dxe4 30. Rc2 Rd8 31. Qe2 Rd3 32. Qxe4
Rcxc3 33. Rxc3 Rxc3 $15) 28... dxc4 $1 (28... bxc4 29. Qg3 d4 30. Ra5 {leaves
Black rooks without any job}) 29. Qe2 Rd7 {with an easy initiative play}) 28.
Qxd2 Rxc3 $2 {Matlakov has fallen exactly in the opponent's trap.} ({Even in
this position the engine suggests sacrificing the d6-pawn with the same idea
to free the bishop.} 28... d5 $1 29. Bxd5 Rxc3 30. Ra7 Rc2 31. Rxf7 (31. Qe3
R8c7 $11) 31... Rxd2 32. Rxf6+ Rxd5 33. Rxf8+ Kxf8 34. exd5 Rc4 35. Rxe5 Rxb4
36. d6 Rd4 37. Rxb5 Rxd6 $14 {This endgame is drawn (see the second game of
the Carlsen-Nepomniachtchi match).}) 29. Re3 $1 {Other moves would give
nothing special.} (29. Bd5 Rc2 30. Qe3 Be7 $11 {and White gets even worse if
he overpushes.} 31. Ra7 $2 R8c3 32. Qb6 Qf4 $1 {The Black's attack develops
faster.} 33. Rxe7 Rc1 $1 34. Bxf7+ Kh7 $19) (29. Qd5 Be7 30. Ra7 Rc1 31. Rd1
Rxd1+ 32. Qxd1 (32. Bxd1 Rc1 $15) 32... Rc3 $11) 29... Rxe3 {The Russian GM
had a choice here - how many rooks to leave on the board. He made a correct
one - fewer rooks, fewer attacking resources.} (29... R3c7 $6 30. Rf3 Qd8 31.
Ra5 {would leave White too many active pieces.}) 30. fxe3 $1 {[#] This is the
whole point of an idea! White voluntarily worsens his pawn structure but gets
one more line to attack f7. Moreover, pawn e3 appears useful to defend d4 and
f4 squares. Black became the defending side. How would you play here as Black?}
Rc7 $2 ({Black misses the last chance to open up Bf8:} 30... d5 $1 31. Bxd5 Rc7
32. Rf1 Qb6 {Queen also enjoys an absence of the pawn on d6.} 33. Qa2 Qxe3+ 34.
Kh2 Bxb4 $11 (34... Qa7 $4 35. Rxf7 $1 Rxf7 (35... Qxa2 36. Rxc7+ Qxd5 37. exd5
$18) 36. Qxa7 $18)) 31. Bd5 $1 $16 {The England GM used a chance to block both
the a3-f8 diagonal and the 6th rank. A defense becomes more and more difficult
for the Russian GM.} g6 32. Qd3 Qg5 33. Rf1 h5 $2 {Black missed the chance to
occupy the best square for the queen (at least temporarily):} ({The correct
way was} 33... Qg3 $1 {White should make a move back:} 34. Qd2 $1 $14 {(to
prepare Rf3) that is never easy for a chess player.}) 34. Rf3 {[#] White
improves his rook without moving the queen back, which means bad news for the
pawn on b5.} Qh4 $2 {No sense move.} ({The last chance to defend was} 34... Kh7
$1 35. Qxb5 Rc2 $1 36. Qf1 Kh6 37. b5 Rb2 {reaching the maximum activity for
own pieces.} 38. Kh2 $16) 35. Kh2 $1 $18 Bh6 36. Qxb5 Kh7 37. Qe8 Bg7 38. Bxf7
Re7 39. Qd8 {Black resigned.} 1-0

