{[#] White has a better position but there would be a long fight ahead if
Black had not weakened the d5-square.} 22... e5 $2 23. Ne2 $1 b5 {Black's
hopes were connected with this attack on c4. But Andersson gave us one more
lesson on how to handle the material in the middlegames with the
opposite-colored bishops.} 24. axb5 axb5 25. Nc3 $1 bxc4 26. b4 Rc7 27. Nd5 {
[#]} Nxd5 $2 ({Pawn c4 plays no role in the position. But it is going to be
hard to stop the b-pawn. Especially if the White bishop will arrive at d5.
That's why Black's only option was an exchange sacrifice with an idea to
restrict the bishop.} 27... e4 $1 28. Nxc7 Qxc7 29. b5 $16) 28. Bxd5 $18 {
To win,, White needs to improve his major pieces and advance the b-pawn. Black
can't do anything.} Qb8 29. b5 Rc5 30. b6 Rec8 31. e4 g6 32. Qb4 R8c6 33. Rb1 {
Bd5 is more than a rook.} Rc8 34. Qa4 {Black resigned because there were no
chances against a GM in such a position. Let's understand what might happen if
Black made a few more moves.} Rd8 {(to prevent Qd7).} 35. Qa7 $1 Qxa7 36. bxa7
Ra5 (36... Rxd5 37. exd5 Ra8 38. Rb7 $18) 37. Rb8 $18 1-0

