{[#] Here, I offer you to look at the way how Black helped his opponent to get
a strong bishop. Everything began with a move} 22... b4 $6 ({It seems so
natural to play b5-b4 with a bishop on g7 but it is too early here. Black had
to move the queen away from the h2-b8 diagonal} 22... Qb6 $5) 23. c4 Ne7 24.
Bf4 $1 {a critical move that locks down Bg7 and weakens the d5-square.} e5 25.
Be3 Nc6 $6 {Another wrong move that places the N under tempo move. It was
better to direct the N to d4 via f5 (where it could not be attacked).} 26. Qa4
$1 Nd4 $2 {The series of mistakes is over. Black did everything White could
dream about. Any defense on c6 would be stronger (in order to avoid the
exchange of Be3 to Black N).} 27. Bd5 Qc7 28. Bxd4 exd4 29. Re4 $16 {White is
much better.} *

