[WhiteClock "0:18:53"]
[BlackClock "0:47:12"]

{[#] Pawn on b2 is attacked and White is forced to play} 35. b4 {Black must be
extremely cautious in this situation because he has no light-squared bishop.
For this reason, it was necessary to keep the c4-pawn blocked. For this
purpose 35...Nb7 would be fine. But Black undervalued the power of the
opponent's bishop. A reminder: when one side has a bishops pair advantage, the
opponent should worry more about the bishop with no opposition.} cxb4 $2 {
Practically a decisive mistake.} (35... Nb7 $1 36. b5 Nca5 {might be played
instead. Bb1 would be seriously restricted in this case.}) 36. c5 $1 {The
a2-g8 diagonal is ready for use.} Nb5 37. axb4 Bf6 ({Black could complicate an
appearance of the bishop on the critical diagonal by playing} 37... Na3 {After}
38. Qxa6 {Black can't take on b4 but he can regroup to attack it anew.} Ra8 {
[#] The important moment. Where to retreat?} 39. Qe2 Reb8 {Pawn b4 is attacked
and there is no obvious way to defend it. But the next move helps us to see
why e2 was the best square for the queen.} 40. h4 $1 {It appears so, that pawn
b4 can't be taken and White can slowly increase pressure on the kingside (Rh1,
h4-h5 and so on).} Nxb4 $2 41. Bxb4 Rxb4 42. Ba2 $1 $18 {Here it is! Black is
hopeless.}) 38. Bd3 Nc3 39. Bxc3 dxc3 40. Bc4 Qe7 41. Rxc3 Rxb4 42. Bd5 $18 {
The result is decided; a weakness on a6, a passed c-pawn, and of course, a
difference between bishops leaving Black no saving hopes.} Nd4 43. Qxa6 Qc7 44.
Nxd4 exd4 45. Rc2 g5 46. Qd3 Be5 47. Ra1 Qe7 48. Ra6 Rf8 49. c6 Rbb8 50. Rca2
Rbc8 51. Ra7 Rc7 52. Rb7 $1 g6 53. Qd2 Rfc8 54. Rxc7 Rxc7 55. h4 $1 gxh4 56.
Qh6 {Black resigned.} 1-0

