{[#] The Polish GM got a nice position with Bb3 putting pressure on the
f7-square. But at the moment, his R is under attack and Black hopes to play
Rfd8 on the next move to prevent Rd7 appearance.} 25. Rd7 $1 {Duda correctly
evaluated that even a win of the exchange would not help his opponent to
escape. White pieces will be too active if Black takes on e5.} ({After} 25.
Red5 {Black would have saving hopes in the pawn down endgame:} Rfd8 26. Rd7
Rxd7 27. Rxd7 Kf8 28. Rxb7 Na5 $1 29. Rxa7 Nxb3 30. axb3 Rb8 31. Ne5 Rxb3 $16 {
though, technically this also should be lost for Black.}) 25... Bd8 {Black
didn't dare to accept a gift, which means White set the R on d7 for free.} ({
In case of} 25... Nxe5 26. Nxe5 Bxg5 {White has a choice of the winning
continuations.} 27. Nxg6 $18 (27. Nxf7 $18)) 26. Rb5 Na5 ({A hopeless position
arises if Black defends on b7 by means of} 26... b6 27. Ne5 $1 {exchanges the
most active opponent's piece.} Nxe5 28. Rxe5 Rc7 29. Bxf7+ Kg7 30. Be8+ Rxd7
31. Bxd7 $18 {White wins by advancing his "e" and "f" pawns.}) 27. Bd5 (27.
Rxd8 $1 {looks even simpler} Nxb3 28. Rxf8+ Kxf8 29. Rxb3 $18) 27... Rc7 28.
Bxf7+ $1 Kg7 (28... Rxf7 29. Rxd8+ $18) 29. Rxc7 Bxc7 30. Bd5 ({Black resigned
because White has a free pawn and dominates on the board.} 30. Bd5 Bb6 (30...
b6 31. Nd4 $18) 31. Ne5 $18 {followed by Be4, f2-f4.}) *

