{[#] To fix the big advantage, White had to take under control the light
squares on the kingside.} 34. Qd1 $1 {with an idea of Qg4. Black would have
serious problems.} ({Moreover, this move also would prevent the Black's idea,
which happened in the game:} 34. Qd3 $2 Qg6 $1 35. Qe2 g4 $1 {with the pawn on
g4 Black feels more confident in the center and on the kingside.} 36. Bd3 Re5
37. Rh1 Bf6 38. Qd2 Qg7 39. Qb2 (39. Qf4 Qg5 40. Kf1 $1 $16) 39... Re8 40. Rh5
Re5 41. Rxe5 Bxe5 42. Qe2 Qg5 43. Qd1 Qg6 {Agreed for a draw.}) {Let's see
some lines that might occur after 34.Qd1.} 34... Kf8 35. Qg4 d3 (35... Qe7 36.
e5 $1 Bxe5 37. f4 $18) 36. Bxd3 Qd4 37. Re3 Qxb4 38. Qxg5 Qd4 ({or} 38... Qxa5
39. Bc4 $18 {followed by Rf3, Qh5.}) 39. Bc2 $1 $18 {White bishop anyway comes
to the a2-g8 diagonal.} *

