{Middlegames with opposite-colored bishops (part III) Which opening comes to
mind when you think about bad bishops? I guess many of you will answer the
“French defence”. For me, it is definitely so. After the moves 1.e4 e6 2.
d4 d5 Black’s light-squared bishop is doomed to experience long-lasting
difficulties in finding a good place on the board. True French experts such as
Viktor Kortschnoj, Wolfgang Uhlmann, Jan Timman, Rafael Vaganian were, in
their best games, even able to make this bishop an important asset but in most
French games the bishop struggles to be effective. Sometimes White manages to
trump this bishop with the knight on d4. But for our series, these examples do
not have a particular value. We are specifically interested in the situations
when the dominance of White’s dark-squared achieves an advantage bishop.
There are a few typical scenarios where such an advantage occurs. Let’s
research them! Quite often, an advantage is obtained due to securing control
of the a3-f8 diagonal and trapping the king in the center of the board.
Let’s see a few relevant games. (Normally, authors omit the opening moves of
the strategic examples, but I decided to make an exception for this article
because we talk about specifics of the concrete opening. Probably you will be
able to apply described ideas in your 1.e4 games).} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. a4 Nbc6 8. Nf3 Qc7 ({The modern
opening theory advices} 8... Qa5 {entering the endgame after} 9. Qd2 Bd7 10.
Ba3 cxd4 11. cxd4 Qxd2+ 12. Kxd2 {with better chances for White.}) 9. Bd3 ({
Immediate capture of the diagonal} 9. Ba3 {was probably even stronger but
Vasiukov preferred the idea of the pawn sacrifice.}) 9... cxd4 {Black accepted
the challenge and took the pawn.} 10. O-O ({The interesting rapid game has
been played by Alexey Shirov and Anton Korobov.} 10. cxd4 Nb4 $6 ({seemingly,
Black needs to take the pawn by means of} 10... Nxd4 $5) 11. O-O Bd7 12. Ba3
Nxd3 13. cxd3 {This capture should not confuse you; it has a few advantages
for White – removing the weakness from c2, control of c4-square, and a
chance to fight for the c-file.} Bc6 14. Nh4 O-O 15. f4 f5 16. exf6 Rxf6 {
[#] An instructive exchange moment.} 17. g3 $2 ({It was better to take on e7
first.} 17. Bxe7) 17... Be8 $2 (17... Nf5 $1 {would leave the bishop useless
on the a3-f8 diagonal and after} 18. Nxf5 exf5 {could help Black to solve all
his problems. This is why it was necessary to take on e7 on the previous move.}
) 18. Bxe7 $1 Qxe7 19. Qd2 $14 {White got a stable advantage and later
converted it in the whole point; Shirov, A-Korobov,A, Warsaw (rapid), 2010.})
10... dxc3 {Black took two pawns but did nothing for his development. Now
everything depends on whether Black manages to solve the king's problem or not.
} 11. Re1 Ng6 {[#]} ({A useful idea for such positions might be the creating
of the outpost on b4.} 11... a5 $5) 12. Bxg6 {White decided to defend the
e5-pawn by the exchange of the knight g6. But there was a stronger option.} (
12. Ra3 $1 Ncxe5 $2 {is bad due to} ({after} 12... Nb4 {White can push his
h-pawn since nothing already threatens the e5-pawn.} 13. h4 $44) 13. Nxe5 Nxe5
14. Bf4 f6 {[#] Here, White can sacrifice the exchange; it guarantees the
central position for the bishop and disconnects the Black rooks for a long
period.} 15. Rxe5 $1 fxe5 16. Qh5+ Qf7 17. Bb5+ Kf8 18. Qxe5 $16) 12... hxg6
13. Ba3 Ne7 $6 ({I would suggest Black to play against Ba3 by a move} 13... Na5
$5 {followed by Nc4.}) 14. Nd4 $6 ({There was nothing special to do on d4. It
was important to have a support of the e5-pawn. Instead, White could attack
the c3-pawn.} 14. Re3 $1 Nf5 15. Rd3 Bd7 16. g4 $1 $44 {followed by Bd6}) 14...
Bd7 15. Re3 Rc8 16. Qg4 Rh5 $2 ({Black might underline a weak position of Nd4
by means of} 16... Qb6 $1 {and then Rc4.}) 17. Bd6 Qc4 $2 {[#]} ({An untimely
activity. If Breustedt had seen what his opponent had had in his mind, he
would defend on e7 by a move} 17... Qd8) 18. Rh3 $1 {Unexpectedly, White is
already near the Black king.} Rh6 ({After} 18... Rxh3 19. Qxh3 {Black can
avoid the back rank checkmate} Bxa4 {but White wins with a tactic on the
e6-square.} 20. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 21. Qxe6 Rc7 22. Bxc7 Qxc7 23. Rxa4 $18) 19. Rh4
$2 ({Vasiukov didn't make use of the unprotected position of Ne7. The point is
that after} 19. Qg5 $1 {Black should put his knight on g8, which definitely
was not his plan.} Ng8 $8 20. Rd3 $14) 19... Ng8 $2 ({It is not easy to
understand what Black might dislike about a move} 19... Nf5 $1 20. Nxf5 ({or} 
20. Qg5 Nxd6 21. exd6 f6 22. Qg3 Rxh4 23. Qxh4 Kf7 $19) 20... exf5 (20... Qxg4
$2 21. Nxg7+ $1 Kd8 22. Rxg4 Rh7 23. Nxe6+ Bxe6 24. Rb4 $16) 21. Qxc4 Rxc4 22.
Rxc4 dxc4 $17) 20. Qg3 $1 Qa6 {Black took his Q back from the 4th rank. In the
exercises part you will have a chance to find what White threatened in this
position.} 21. Rf4 $1 $16 {[#] Rh6 and Ng8 are out.} f5 $1 {Black tries to
grab at least some squares for his own pieces (especially for the king).} 22.
h3 Rc4 23. a5 Kf7 24. Nf3 $1 {Vasiukov directed his N to g5, which was a smart
decision.} Qc6 25. Rb1 Bc8 26. Rxc4 Qxc4 ({Or} 26... dxc4 27. Ng5+ Ke8 28. Qxc3
$18) 27. Ng5+ Ke8 {[#]} 28. Nxe6 $1 {Vasiukov decided to end the game nicely.}
Bxe6 29. Rxb7 {Black can't do anything against Qg5 threat.} Qc6 30. Rxg7 d4 31.
Qg5 Qd7 32. Rxd7 Kxd7 33. Qf4 Ne7 34. Qxh6 {Black resigned. This game had many
mistakes but thanks to the difference between the bishops. White always had
sufficient compensation for the pawns.} 1-0

