{Janis Klovans and Alexey Kosikov played two interesting games by the same
variation in 1974 and 1977. In the first game, Kosikov couldn’t defend well
and lost fairly quickly; he prepared an improvement and took the revenge for
the second game.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7
7. Nf3 Qc7 8. a4 Nbc6 9. Be2 cxd4 10. cxd4 Nb4 11. O-O $6 ({Only in 1988 the
correct move was played (in the correspondent game).} 11. Rb1 $1 {White
provokes a7-a5 that seriously weakens the Black's position.} a5 (11... Nxc2+ $4
12. Kd2 $18 {and knight is trapped.}) 12. Kd2 Bd7 13. c3 Nbc6 14. Ba3 $18 {
with a perfect position, Decker,M-Kell,S corr 1988}) 11... Qxc2 12. Qe1 {[#]}
a5 $1 {In the annotation to the previous game I have already mentioned this
idea. An outpost on b4 should resolve Black's problems on the a3-f8 diagonal.}
({In the first game Kosikov played} 12... Nd3 $2 {and after} 13. Bxd3 Qxd3 14.
Ba3 {White got practically a winning position.} Nc6 15. Qc1 f6 16. Re1 Kf7 17.
exf6 gxf6 18. Qf4 h6 19. Re3 Qh7 {[#]} 20. Ne5+ $1 {A good check, that weakens
almost all dark squares on the Black's half.} Nxe5 21. dxe5 f5 22. Qh4 Ke8 23.
Qf6 Rg8 24. Rg3 {Black resigned; Klovans, J - Kosikov, A, URS, 1974. The
beautiful checkmate could happen after} Rxg3 25. Qf8+ Kd7 26. Rc1 $1 Rxa3 27.
Rc7+ Kxc7 28. Qd6# {[#]}) 13. Ba3 ({In the game Zhao,J-Drozdovskij,Y, Cochin
2004 White decided to exchange the French bishop (that does not make any sense)
and got the worse position:} 13. Bb5+ $2 Bd7 14. Ba3 Bxb5 15. axb5 Nd3 16. Qd1
Rc8 $17 {with no real compensation for the pawn.}) 13... Bd7 14. Bd1 Qc7 15.
Bxb4 axb4 16. Qxb4 {[#] Opponents has restored the status quo – White took a
pawn back, Black exchanged the dark-squared bishop. To achieve a full equality
Black needs to make a short castling.} Nc6 17. Qa3 b5 18. Bc2 b4 19. Qd3 {
[#] White had hoped that trapping the king in the center would help him to get
the advantage. But the French bishop had another opinion on this issue.} Bc8 $1
20. Rfc1 Ba6 21. Qd2 {and here} O-O {would secure Black a better position. In
the game, Black played 21...Bc4. As I said earlier, Kosikov took revenge in
this game but it is already another story. We move to a new example with the
opposite-colored bishops.} *

