{Now I offer you to look at the game of Boris Spassky who managed to
convincingly outclass one of the French experts.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4
4. e5 Ne7 5. Qg4 {A more popular continuation is 5.a3. Spassky decided to
begin with an attack on the g7-pawn.} c5 6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Qc7 {A double
attack – on c3 and e5.} 8. Bb5+ Nbc6 {[#]} ({A quick tragedy happened with
White in the next game.} 8... Bd7 {A logical attempt to exchange own worst
piece.} 9. O-O Bxc3 10. Bxd7+ $4 ({The correct way to give up a pawn was} 10.
bxc3 $14 {holding the Black knight on b8.}) 10... Nxd7 11. Nb5 ({or} 11. bxc3
Qxc3 12. Rb1 Nxe5 $1 13. Qxg7 $2 {[#]} Nf3+ $1 {Nice geometry!} 14. gxf3 Rg8
$19) 11... Qb6 12. Nxc3 O-O 13. Re1 {White avoided the material loses but his
position is terrible.} Rfc8 14. a4 Rc4 15. Qh3 Rac8 $19 {Friedel,J (2328)
-Mamedyarov,S (2595) Chalkidiki 2003}) 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Bd7 ({After} 10...
Qxe5 {White might play} 11. Ba3 Bd7 12. Bxc6 bxc6 {with the game position.})
11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Ba3 ({White didn't like the idea to be pushed back after} 12.
Qxg7 Rg8 13. Qf6 Rg6 14. Qf4 c5 {but the position would remain much better
even here} 15. Nb3 $16) 12... Qxe5 $2 ({The engine recommends taking on e5 in
another way.} 12... c5 13. Nb3 Qxe5 {but it is hard to name the position after}
14. Bxc5 {easy to play for Black.} (14. Nxc5 $2 {allows Black to reach the
comfortable position by means of} Qxc3 15. Bb4 Qc4 $1 16. Qxc4 dxc4 17. Ne4 Nf5
$1 18. g4 Bc6 $1 $15 {an important intermediate move.})) 13. Rfe1 h5 (13... Qf6
{would not guarantee Black 0-0.} 14. Qg3 $1 ({or} 14. Rab1 $1 O-O $2 15. Rb7
Rfd8 16. Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Nxc6 $18) 14... O-O $2 15. Qd6 $18) 14. Qf3 Qc7 {[#]} ({
after} 14... Qf6 {White would save the queens on the board by playing} 15. Qg3
$14) {It is time to break through the opponent's center.} 15. c4 $1 Rb8 $2 ({
And Black immediately has failed. Again and again, we see that to feel fine
Black should try to restrict the White bishop. This time the blockade might be
set on the c5-square.} 15... c5 $1 16. cxd5 $1 O-O $1 ({after} 16... cxd4 $2
17. dxe6 $18 {Ra8 is also hanging.}) 17. dxe6 fxe6 18. Qe4 cxd4 19. Bxe7 Rfe8
20. Bf6 $1 $14 {followed by Be5; White is better but the main fight is ahead.})
16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Bxe7 {Yes, sometimes we need to say goodbye to our favorite
bishop.} Kxe7 18. Nf5+ Kd8 ({Black needed to give up on g7 because a try to
save this pawn would turn into big problems for his king:} 18... Kf8 $2 19.
Qa3+ Kg8 20. Ne7+ Kh7 21. Qf3 $1 Kh6 22. Qxf7 Qxc2 23. Rac1 Qd3 24. Re5 g6 {[#]
} 25. Rf5 $1 $18 {there were other winning moves but this one is the most
spectacular.}) 19. Nxg7 $18 {White is winning but the game text gets out of
our topic (no opposite-coloured bishops left), that's why I offer to move to a
new game.} *

