{To continue the topic of the a3-f8 diagonal, I offer a game between two
Russian Grandmasters. White initially got an almost decisive advantage in this
one, but one inaccuracy was enough for Black to get back to the fight.} 1. e4
e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 Ne7 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 {The main move is 6...
c5 but Pavel's move is also playable. Black aims to resolve his main problem
– Bc8-a6.} 7. Qg4 Ng6 {Modern engines dislike the Ne7-g6 idea (in all of its
modifications) and it is hard to disagree with them. But one thing is to know
the evaluation of the position and another thing is to prove the correctness
of this evaluation.} 8. h4 $1 {White weakens the position of the knight.} h5 9.
Qf3 Qd7 ({After} 9... Ba6 {White can go to take the pawn on h5.} 10. Bxa6 Nxa6
11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Ne2 $16 {followed by Ng3xh5.}) 10. a4 ({A brave computer takes
on h5 by playing} 10. Ne2 {even in this situation.}) 10... c5 $2 {This move
disabled Ba6 and this was bad news for Black.} ({The point of the last White's
move was to prepare for Ba6:} 10... Ba6 11. Bxa6 Nxa6 12. a5 $14 {with an
active position. But anyway, it was the best try for Black.}) 11. Bb5 Nc6 12.
a5 Qc7 13. Ne2 Bd7 {[#] White had to decide what to do next and Igor Kurnosov
has handled this exercise well.} 14. axb6 $1 Qxb6 15. Bxc6 $1 Qxc6 16. Ba3 $18
{There is perfect domination of Ba3 against the French bishop. The position is
technically winning but Pavel Ponkratov is known for his high fighting skills.
Let's see how he defended in this tough position.} cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxe5 18. Qg3 {
White needs to make 0-0 to get the absolutely winning position. In this reason
Black played} Qc4 $1 {preventing 0-0. [#]} ({A passive move} 18... Qc7 $2 {
allowed the White king to get castled.} 19. O-O $18) 19. Kd2 $2 {Kurnosov
played the natural move but it was a mistake.} ({After the correct move} 19.
Bb4 $1 {Black could not hold the knight on e5.} Ng6 ({or} 19... Nc6 20. Nxc6
Bxc6 (20... Qxc6 21. O-O $18) 21. Qd6 $18) ({after} 19... Qc7 {White readily
makes the castling.} 20. O-O $18) 20. Kd2 {The difference is that now Black
knight does not come to c4.} a5 21. Rhe1 Z0 $18) 19... Qc7 20. Kc1 O-O-O 21.
Re1 Nc4 $13 {Position became unclear.} 22. Be7 {White aims to take a pawn back
(on a7).} Qxg3 23. fxg3 a5 $1 {A brave idea that had to work well.} ({After} 
23... Rde8 {White could take on a7} 24. Rxa7) 24. Bxd8 Rxd8 25. Nb3 a4 26. Nc5
a3 $2 {A pawn will not survive there. It was better to keep it on a4 under the
protection of the B.} (26... Kc7 $1 $44 27. Nxa4 $4 Ra8 $19) 27. Nb3 $1 {
White goes to exchange Nc4 and to win on a3.} Kc7 28. Nd2 Nxd2 $2 (28... Ra8 {
was the best way to defend.} 29. Nxc4 dxc4 30. Re4 Ra4 $14) 29. Kxd2 Ra8 30.
Reb1 Kd6 31. Rb3 a2 32. Rb2 $16 {Technically the position looks winning.} *

