{To avoid thinking that placing the bishop on a3 means an automatic win we
will look at the next game.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+
6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Qg4 O-O 8. Qh3 {In my database, this move has been played twice
(in 1956 and 2007). The reason is that White has other good moves – 8.Bd3
and 8.Nf3.} Nbc6 9. Bd3 Ng6 10. Nf3 c4 11. Bxg6 fxg6 12. a4 Qa5 {[#]} 13. Kd2
$2 {White wanted to place the bishop on a3 at any cost.} ({A typical French
exchange sacrifice might happen in case of} 13. Bb2 Rxf3 $1 14. Qxf3 Nxd4 15.
Qd1 Nc6 $44) ({Seemingly, the best was} 13. Bd2 {which would bring the bishop
away from the desirable a3-square.} b5 $13) 13... b5 $1 14. Ba3 {Bishop has
come to a3 but it was the last White's achievement in this game.} b4 $1 15.
cxb4 c3+ $1 ({Probably White missed this intermediate move and his
consideration was} 15... Nxb4 $4 16. c3 Nd3 17. Bxf8 $18) 16. Kxc3 Qxa4 $19 {
[#] White has a free pawn but his king is weak, the bishop is blocked, the
light squares are extremely weak – Black is winning.} 17. Rhb1 Qb5 18. Kd2
Rf5 ({An active} 18... Rf4 {was much stronger.}) 19. Rb3 Ba6 20. Re1 ({The
best defense was to evacuate the king to the queenside.} 20. Rc3 $5 Qe2+ 21.
Kc1 Bc4 22. Qh4 $17) 20... Qb6 21. g4 Rf4 22. Bb2 Bc4 23. Rbe3 Qxb4+ 24. Bc3
Qb6 {Black took the pawn back and even increased his own positional advantage
- the f-file became weak and he got a passed pawn. Ten moves later, White
resigned.} *

[Event "RUS-chT 9th"]
