{If the Black king manages to castle to the short side, it does not mean that
Black will be fine. The king can still be attacked. In the Steinitz variation,
it often happens that White castles to the queenside and advances his kingside
pawns. A good illustration of this scenario occurred in the game of 8-times
Russian Champion Peter Svidler.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e5 Nfd7 5. f4
c5 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Qd2 O-O 10. O-O-O Bxd4 11. Bxd4 a6 {
[#]} 12. Bf2 $5 {Since White is strategically better (mostly because of the
French bishop) Svidler aims to simplify the position with a maneuver of his
knight to d4.} b5 13. Ne2 b4 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 a5 {With the bishop on d4
White feels good on both king and queen sides. On the kingside, it makes it
disadvantageous for Black the f7-f6 move; on the queenside, it helps to defend
the White king.} 16. g4 Qc7 17. Bb5 {[#]} ({Objectively speaking, a move} 17.
Kb1 {was more consistent.}) 17... Ba6 $2 {Black misevaluated the importance of
leaving the knight on the board. An opposite-colored bishops middlegame
without other minor pieces turns into a total disaster for Black because White
is a side that has the initiative.} ({The correct move was} 17... Nc5 $1 {
followed by Ba6. Black was not worse there.}) 18. Bxd7 $1 Qxd7 19. Rhg1 {
White prepares an assault.} Rfc8 20. f5 Qb5 21. Rg2 ({White prevented the Qe2
idea. At first sight, it looks like the necessary action, but White's pressure
on the kingside does not weaken without queens. A few moves later Svidler
realizes this fact.} 21. f6 $1 Qe2 22. Rge1 Qxd2+ 23. Rxd2 $18) 21... b3 22.
axb3 Qxb3 23. f6 Qb4 {[#]} ({The engine suggests here to defend against Qg5 by
a move} 23... Qh3 {but the resulting endgame remains the same terrible for
Black:} 24. Qg5 Qh6 25. Qxh6 gxh6 26. Kd2 $18) 24. Qxb4 $1 (24. Qg5 g6 25. Qh6
Qf8 26. Qxf8+ Kxf8 27. Kd2 {was not the same good. In the game, White
additionally created a weakness on b4 and left no real active options for
Black on the queenside.}) 24... axb4 25. b3 $1 $18 {The rest is relatively
simple.} gxf6 (25... g6 {would not leave many saving chances for Black.} 26. g5
$1 {Fixing the h7-pawn.} Kf8 27. Kb2 Ke8 28. Rdd2 (28. Rg4 $4 Be2) 28... Kd7
29. Rg4 $18 {followed by a doubling of the rooks on the h-file.}) 26. exf6 Rc6
27. g5 Kf8 28. h4 Ke8 29. h5 Rac8 30. Be5 Kd7 31. Kb1 Rg8 {[#] It is time for
decisive actions.} 32. g6 $1 hxg6 33. hxg6 Rxg6 34. Rxg6 fxg6 35. Rh1 Rc8 36.
Rh7+ Kc6 37. Re7 d4 38. f7 d3 39. cxd3 Bxd3+ 40. Kb2 Kd5 41. Rc7 {followed by
Bg7. Black resigned.} 1-0

