{The Cuban-born American GM Leinier Dominguez showed us a good example of
generating a kingside attack with the same side castling.} 1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Qg4 O-O 8. Bd3 Nbc6 9. Bg5 $5 {
Not the most popular continuation but definitely a dangerous one.} Qa5 10. Ne2
Ng6 (10... c4 $2 11. Bxh7+ Kxh7 12. Qh4+ $18 {and Bxe7.}) 11. O-O c4 ({As an
alternative for Black a move} 11... Qa4 $5 {might be recommended.}) 12. Bxg6
fxg6 13. a4 $1 $16 {[#] A technical move that grants the a3-square for the
bishop.} Qc7 ({Peter Leko visually easily got the winning position in his
blitz game against Aleksandr Morozevich.} 13... Bd7 14. h4 Rf7 15. Rfb1 b6 16.
f3 Raf8 17. Kf2 h6 18. Bc1 Kh7 19. Ba3 Rc8 20. Bb4 Qa6 21. Nf4 $18 {Leko,P -
Morozevich,A Doha 2016}) 14. Bc1 $1 Qf7 15. Ng3 ({White prevented the Qf5-idea
but a deeper look shows that the endgame would be tough for Black:} 15. Ba3 $1
Qf5 16. Qxf5 Rxf5 17. h4 $16 {followed by f2-f3, Kf2-e3, g2-g4 and so on.})
15... Bd7 16. f3 {The White king frees the way for the rook.} (16. Ba3 {
seemingly has not been played because of} Qf4 {though we already know that the
endgame was not easy for Black:} 17. Qxf4 Rxf4 18. Ne2 $16) 16... Rfc8 17. h4
Be8 18. Kf2 Ne7 19. Rh1 Nf5 {[#]} 20. Ne2 $1 {White is going to push Nf5 back;
so, no need to exchange the knights.} Rc6 $1 {With a series of technical moves
Artur Jussupow created a counterplay against the a4-pawn.} 21. Qh3 Ra6 22. g4
Ne7 23. a5 Nc6 $2 {A decisive mistake.} ({Black could attack the a5-pawn by
his b7-pawn to leave the knight near his king.} 23... b6 $1 $13 {The end of
this game you can find in the exercises part.}) *

