{The last example I wanted to share in this article occurs when the Black king
runs away to the queenside. In this case, the difference between the bishops
is less tangible because the White bishop usually has not so much to do. But
if White organizes an attack on the queenside, Black appears in big danger.} 1.
e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. e5 c5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Ne7 7. Nf3 Bd7 8. dxc5
$5 {A typical decision for the French defense. White worsens his own pawn
structure in order to make the Bc1 more perspective.} Qa5 9. Bd3 Na6 $1 ({
White gets a decent compensation for a pawn after} 9... Qxc3+ 10. Bd2 Qxc5 11.
Bb4 Qc7 12. O-O Nbc6 13. Bd6) 10. O-O Nxc5 11. Rb1 h6 $11 {[#] Black prevents
both Bg5 and Ng5.} 12. Rb4 $1 {A good move that prepares White for both of
possible castlings.} O-O-O $2 {The experienced Russian GM misevaluated a power
of the attack on the queen side.} ({Black had to delay a castling.} 12... Rc8
$1 13. Re1 (13. Nd4 Qc7 14. Re1 {and now} O-O {does not cause major problems
for Black.}) (13. Rg4 $2 Nxd3 14. cxd3 Qxc3 15. Rxg7 Nf5 16. Rg4 Bb5 $19) 13...
Qc7 {with an unclear play.}) (12... O-O $6 {also was not a perfect decision:}
13. Rg4 $1 (13. Bxh6 gxh6 14. Rg4+ Ng6 $1 {and Black is fine.} (14... Kh8 $4
15. Qd2 Ng8 16. Rxg8+ Kxg8 17. Qxh6 Ne4 18. Ng5 $18)) 13... Nf5 14. Nd4 {
with a dangerous attack.} Qxc3 $4 15. Bxf5 exf5 16. Rg3 Qc4 17. Bxh6 $18) 13.
Nd4 Kb8 14. Qg4 Nxd3 ({An instant} 14... Rhg8 {would fail because of} 15. Bh7
$18 {followed by 16.Qxg7.}) 15. cxd3 Rhg8 16. Be3 Ka8 17. Qf3 Rgf8 $2 {[#]} ({
A counterattack on e5 was practically the last chance} 17... Ng6 18. Rfb1 b6
$16) {Black's position looks solid but the next two moves underline a presence
of the opposite-colored bishops on the board.} 18. Nb3 $1 Qc7 19. Bc5 Bc6 20.
Nd4 Rde8 21. Rfb1 {Black is completely outplayed. A concrete threat is to play
Bd6, Nxc6 and Rxb7.} b6 {[#]} 22. Bxb6 $1 (22. Bd6 Qd7 23. a4 {was also good
but the bishop's sacrifice decides the game at once.}) 22... axb6 23. Rxb6 Qa7
({After} 23... Bb7 24. Qd1 {wins}) 24. Nxc6 Nxc6 25. Rxc6 $18 {White is
winning thanks to two extra pawns.} *

