{[#] White energetically takes total control over the dark squares on the king
side.} 24. h5 $1 Rxa5 ({There is no a defense after} 24... gxh5 25. Nf4 $1 (25.
gxh5 $2 {is a mistake because of} h6 26. Rg1 Kh7 {and attack does not go so
easy}) 25... Rxa5 (25... Ne7 26. Nxh5 Qg6 27. Ra2 $18 {followed by Nf4, Qh4
etc.}) 26. Rxa5 Nxa5 27. gxh5 h6 (27... Bd7 $2 28. h6 g6 29. Nxg6 $1 hxg6 (
29... Qxg6 30. Rg1 $18) 30. h7+ Kh8 31. Bg5 $18) 28. Qxe6 $1 Qxe6 29. Nxe6 Bf7
30. Nf4 Re8 31. Re1 $18 {followed by e5-e6 and Nxd5.}) 25. Rxa5 Nxa5 26. h6 $1
{This is the idea of the h-pawn march.} Ba4 27. hxg7 Qxg7 28. Bg5 $18 {and
White pieces massively occupy the weakened squares. Let me share the last
moves of this game to show you the spectacular final.} Bxc2 29. Nf4 Re8 30. Bf6
Qd7 31. Qh6 Nc6 32. Nh5 Rf8 33. Ng7 g5 34. Nxe6 Re8 35. Qxg5+ Bg6 {[#]} 36.
Qxg6+ {Black resigned because of checkmate in 2.} hxg6 37. Rh8+ Kf7 38. Ng5# *

