{[#]} 29... Rxf4 $3 ({In the game Black didn't feel a moment and played a slow
move} 29... Bc6 $2 30. Bd4 $14) 30. gxf4 Qg6+ 31. Bg3 {Other lines are not
difficult.} (31. Kf1 Bh3#) (31. Kh1 Nxf3 $1 32. Rxe7 (32. Qf1 Nxh2 $1 33. Kxh2
(33. Rxe7 Nxf1 34. Rxf1 d4 $1 35. Rxd7 Qc6+ $19) 33... Qh5+ 34. Kg1 Rxe2 $19)
32... Nxe1 33. Rdxe1 d4 $1 {With an idea of Bc6.} 34. Rxd7 Qc6+ $19) 31... Nxf3
$1 32. Kxf3 (32. Rxe7 Nxe1+ 33. Rdxe1 d4 $1 {Let me pay your attention to how
often a move d5-d4 followed by Bc6 happens in this combination. Black is
always ready to give up a pawn in order to open up the bishop.} 34. cxd4 Bc6+
35. Kf2 Qxc2+ 36. R1e2 Qd3 $19) (32. Qf2 Rxe2 33. Qxe2 Bg4 $1 {White has no a
satisfactory defense against Black's threats.} 34. Qe3 (34. Qf2 Qe4 $19) 34...
Qxc2+ $19) 32... Bg4+ 33. Kf2 Rxe2+ $19 *

