{[#] White has sacrificed the rook for two connected passed pawns. h5-h6-h7 is
coming and Black needs to find how to stop them. The correct move was} 28...
Bh3 $1 ({In the game Jan Timman played} 28... Qc6 $2 {which didn't stop the
opponent's advancing.} 29. h6 Qe6 30. Bxf4 ({here is the point of the last
Black's moves} 30. h7 $2 Qg4+ 31. Qxg4 Bxg4+ 32. Kc1 Rxg7 $19) 30... Qh3 (30...
Qf5 $5 31. Kd2 Rde8 32. Rh1 Qh7 {Black does not pretend for a win but he
solidly blocks the pawns.}) 31. Kd2 Rde8 (31... Bf5 $2 32. Rh1 Qg4 33. Qxg4
Bxg4 34. Bg5 Rde8 35. Bf6 Bf5 36. h7 Bxh7 37. Rxh7 $18 {followed by Rh8 and a
march of the king to h7.}) 32. Rg1 Re6 33. Rg3 Qh1 34. Qf5 Rxh6 35. Qxf7 Be6
36. Qf8+ Kd7 37. Bg5 $18) 29. h6 Qd7 $1 {This is the correct battery order.
Black moves the bishop to b1-h7 diagonal.} 30. Bxf4 (30. h7 $2 Qg4+ 31. Qxg4+
Bxg4+ 32. Kc1 Rxg7 $19) 30... Bf5 $17 {Black has good winning chances thanks
to having the queen free from the blocking duties.} *

