{[#] The position of the White king does not look safe and David Bronstein
bravely throws his pieces and pawns forward.} 21... Rxh3 $1 22. gxf5 ({A try
to push the rook back would not bring the result:} 22. Kg2 Rxf3 $1 23. Kxf3 (
23. Qxf3 $4 Nh4+) 23... Nh4+ 24. Ke3 ({or} 24. Ke2 $2 e5 25. Kd2 (25. f3 e4 $1
{winning both f3 and g4 pawns.}) 25... e4 $19 {followed by Nf3.}) 24... Ng2+
25. Kd2 Nxe1 26. Qxe1 Qh8 $17 {White has a lot of weak light squares and he is
a pawn down.}) 22... exf5 23. Qe2 ({White could prepare a tricky trap by
playing} 23. Re3 $5 {but Black should not get trapped into it.} Rh6 $1 $19 (
23... f4 $4 24. Nxg5+ fxg5 25. Rxh3 Bxh3 26. Qh5+ $18)) 23... f4 {The French
bishop is ready!} 24. Nd2 Bf5 25. f3 Qh8 $19 (25... Qd7 {followed by Rch8, Bd3
looks simpler and stronger. But anyway, the Black's position remains winning.})
*

