{Middlegames with opposite-colored bishops (part IV) I hope you have studied
the first three articles from this series and some of you already have managed
to beat the opponent with a master play in the position with the
opposite-colored bishops. Let’s continue our research. After dividing all
examples from my collection into three groups (the long diagonal pressure,
a2-g8 (a7-g1) diagonal control, and the French bishop problem), I still saw
many examples left on my computer. A big part of them happened in the Sicilian
games but the rest can hardly be divided into groups with more than 2 examples.
Talking about the Sicilian cases I need to explain how the bad bishop appears
there. In the Sicilian lines with e7-e5, White gets the e4-pawn blocked. If
the White light-squared bishop can’t reach the a2-g8 diagonal  (because his
pawn on c4 or Black manages to prevent Bc4-move), there is a high probability
that the bishop will have to do so become bad. Like the French defense
scenario (described in the previous article) Black can outclass the bishop
with both the knight and own dark-squared bishop. Let’s see how it happens
in detail. First, I offer you the game played by the Hungarian GM Gyula Sax
against Prasad Devaki in the Interzonal of 1987. Let me note that Sax shared
the 1-3 (with Short and Speelman) and qualified to the Candidates matches when
the Indian player could hardly be happy with the overall score (+2-9=4). Still,
he can be proud of one out of his two wins because it was achieved against The
Magician from Riga Mikhail Tal. (For the information, the former World
Champion finished just half a point behind the winners).} 21. b3 $2 {A
positional blunder.} ({White could defend the 2nd rank by a move} 21. Rc2 {
with a good position.}) 21... Ng6 $1 {With an attack on e2, Black trapped the
dark-squared bishop to the exchange.} 22. Bd3 Nxf4 23. Rxf4 g6 {[#] This
position is easy to evaluate. Black has a promising majority on the kingside
and White's majority on the queenside does not give dividends because it is
hard to advance it. Of course, we can't leave without our attention a factor
of the bishops. When the White bishop is restricted by both White and Black
pawns, the Black bishop feels great on the long diagonal and can join the
future attack on the kingside (from e5 or d4).} 24. Re4 {White instinctively
fights for the open file but Be5 will lock it down.} Be5 25. Qh3 f5 26. Re2
Rac8 {Black wants to be sure that there is no c4-c5 idea.} 27. Rf1 Rf8 28. Qh6
Rce8 29. Rfe1 Qc7 {The queen goes to the a7-g1 diagonal.} 30. Qh3 Kg7 31. Bb1
Qc5 32. Qf3 Qd4 {[#] To save the hope for a draw, White had to stay on the
place. Instead, the Indian master decided to fight for the initiative.} 33. Qd3
(33. Qh3 $5) 33... Qh4 34. g3 $2 ({Even here} 34. Qh3 $1 {was better. With a
pawn on g3 Black got so desirable hook to force his own attack.}) 34... Qh5 35.
c5 {There was no a way to prevent f5-f4.} (35. Rf2 Bxg3 $1 36. Rxe8 Rxe8 37.
Qxg3 Re1+ 38. Kg2 Qd1 $1 $19) (35. Rf1 Bxg3 $1 36. Rxe8 Qxh2#) 35... f4 $1 36.
gxf4 ({or} 36. cxd6 fxg3 37. d7 Rd8 $19) 36... Rxf4 37. Rg2 Rh4 38. Ree2 Bxh2
$1 39. Rxh2 Rxe2 {White resigned. After} 40. Qxe2 Qxe2 {his rook can't take on
e2 because of a pin.} 0-1

