{A similar pawn structure happened in the game played by a big Sicilian expert
Evgeny Sveshnikov.  Again we see a situation with a good (perspective) pawn
majority for Black on the kingside and a useless majority for White on the
queenside. So, Black begins his advancing.} 23... f5 24. c3 Qc4 25. a5 e4 26.
Qd1 Qb5 $6 {A move in the wrong direction. On the next few moves, Black moved
back but then still managed to put pressure on the kingside. White's problem
is that he hardly can do anything.} (26... f4 $2 {was weak because of} 27. Qa4
$1 {and Black loses on e4.}) (26... Bf6 $5 {was more consistent.}) 27. Qd2 h6 {
A luft and preparation of Bg5.} 28. Bf1 Qe8 29. Re1 Bg5 30. Qd4 Qd8 31. b4 {
Besides a necessity to follow things on the kingside, White also has a problem
with the a5-b4-c3 pawn chain.} Bf6 32. Qd2 Be5 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} 33. Qe3
$2 {A wrong square for the queen, since here it is under both possible f5-f4
and Bd4 (after c3-c4 move) attacks.} ({Instead of a passive defense of the
c3-pawn, it was necessary to start own counterplay on the queenside -} 33. c4
$1 Qf6 34. Qc2 f4 ({or} 34... Bc3 35. Rb1 Qe5 {Black is ready to push his
f-pawn but White already has his play.} 36. c5 $1 f4 37. c6 {with mutual
chances.}) 35. Rxe4 fxg3 36. hxg3 Bxg3 37. Re2 {and then 38.Bg2 with an
unclear position.}) 33... Qf6 34. Rc1 (34. c4 {already was late because of} Bc3
35. Rb1 Bd4 36. Qd2 f4 {with a strong attack}) 34... h5 $1 {One more pawn
joins the attack. White's defense is hard.} ({An instant} 34... f4 $2 {would
give nothing:} 35. Qxe4 fxg3 36. fxg3 Qf2+ 37. Kh1) 35. f4 $6 {This move leads
to the pawn structure from the first example. We already know that having a
pawn on g3 helps to Black's attack.} ({Seemingly, it was better to play} 35.
Bg2 {but in this case Black also had ways to the White king's residence:} h4
36. Rc2 g5 $5 37. gxh4 g4 $1 $40) 35... exf3 36. Qxf3 Qg5 37. Rc2 f4 {[#] This
is practically over.} 38. h4 {White naturally hopes to survive in the position
without the queens.} Qxg3+ 39. Qxg3 fxg3 40. c4 Rf4 41. c5 Rxh4 $19 {Black is
objectively winning but the end of this game was not so smooth for Black. For
lovers of the endgames, I can offer reading my electronic book "Improving
Endgame Technique" (the part about opposite-colored bishop endgames) where
this endgame is analyzed in detail.} 0-1

