{In this game, we saw a bad “good” bishop on c6. In the notes, I mentioned
that it is a typical situation. Let’s see one more game in which the bishop
maneuver became the critical moment - from the better position. White got the
worse position by bringing her bishop to the c6 square. In the next example,
there were more pieces on the board but a general scenario remained the same -
the kingside pawn majority and the opposite-colored bishops on the board gave
Black a superior position. In the position on the diagram Black prevailed on
the queenside. Normally White would need to have some pawns advanced there,
hoping for some play. On the kingside, Black needs to prepare f7-f5. That will
indicate his advantage. But before preparing f7-f5 Black needs to defend on a6
and to improve his bishop.} 18... Qa7 19. c3 $6 ({White missed a good
opportunity to improve her bishop -} 19. Bb3 $5 {with the idea of Ba4-c6.
Instead, Judit Polgar decided to use the third rank for the rook's maneuvers,
which seemed not a good idea. Attack on the kingside does not look dangerous
for Black.}) 19... bxc3 20. Rxc3 Bd8 $1 {Black used a typical maneuver to
improve the bishop.} 21. Ng5 {Judit Polgar is known for her aggressive style
and here she also tries to attack the opponent's king. But the Black's
position is too solid.} a5 22. Rf3 Qe7 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} 23. b3 ({
Position of White is really tough to play, since earlier or later Black will
advance his pawns in the center. Considering future problems with the knight
on g5 it is easy to advise its exchange.} 23. Ne4 {and after} Nxe4 24. Qxe4 g6
{White at least has some time to place her pieces more compact before the
start of the kingside assault.}) 23... a4 24. Rh3 g6 25. Qc2 ({Black is
solidly better after} 25. Ne4 Nxe4 26. Qxe4 axb3 27. Bxb3 f5 $17) 25... axb3
26. axb3 Bb6 (26... e4 $1 {with an idea of Qe5 would instantly make White's
position critical.} 27. Re1 Qe5 $19 {Though, the move in the game also puts
enough pressure on White's position.}) 27. Rf1 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} ({Here
} 27. Ne4 {is late to play, since the position after} Nxe4 28. Qxe4 Ra2 29. Rf1
Qa7 {followed by f7-f5, e5-e4 is winning for Black. Bc4 is useless.}) 27... Ng4
({One more time} 27... e4 {was a good decision:} 28. Qb2 {Preventing Qe5.} h5
$1 {(threatening Ng4; surprisingly Ng5 faces serious problems to survive).} 29.
Rg3 Ng4 30. Nh3 {Knight is saved, but now} e3 $19 {creates decisive threats to
the monarch; Black is winning. But honestly speaking, now almost any move is
winning for Black, so good his position is.}) 28. Ne4 f5 29. Rg3 Nf6 ({I like
the idea of saving the knights on the board since Black knight will have more
options to be useful. Time that Black loses for this purpose does not really
matter - White is unable to use it for something radical.} 29... Nh6 30. Nc3 e4
{followed by Nh6-f7-e5.}) 30. Nxf6+ Qxf6 31. Rd3 {The rook has not achieved
anything on h3 and returns.} Rc7 32. Qc3 Rca7 33. Rd2 Bd4 34. Qd3 {[#]} Ra1 ({
Black also could add one (or even two) more pawn to attack.} 34... h5 $5) 35.
g3 (35. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 36. Rd1 Ra2 37. Rd2 Ra3 38. Qe2 {was about the same.}) 35...
Rxf1+ 36. Kxf1 (36. Qxf1 $2 Ra1 37. Rd1 Ra2 $19) 36... Bc5 37. Kg2 e4 {Finally,
the e5-pawn makes a move forward.} 38. Qe2 ({After} 38. Qc2 {Black could play}
h5 $5 39. Qb2 Qe7 $17) 38... Re8 {[#]} 39. f3 $2 {Normally, it helps White in
the positions with such pawn structure to exchange the e4-pawn. But in this
concrete situation, f2-f3 opens the file for the rook and makes the Black's
task easier.} ({White could also keep the position closer for a bit longer} 39.
Rd1 {but then Black would probably start the h-pawn run.} h5 $17) 39... exf3+
40. Qxf3 Re3 41. Qf1 (41. Qf4 $2 Re1 $19 {with many ideas such as: Be3, Rg1,
g6-g5-g4.}) 41... Qe5 (41... Qe7 {would save one tempo.}) 42. Qf4 Qe7 43. Ra2
Re1 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} 44. b4 $4 {A blunder that instantly ended the
game.} (44. Bd3 {leaving the 4-th rank for the queen's escape was better.
Though, surely, after} Kg7 $17 {Black would save a big advantage.}) 44... Be3
45. Qf3 Rg1+ 46. Kh3 Qg5 {White resigned because of Qh6 threat.} 0-1

