{An interesting position occurred in the game of the 10th World Champion Boris
Spassky against Vladimir Simagin. By the way, you already saw two examples of
Simagin's technique in the first article of this series. In the position on
the diagram Black has a better pawn structure - passed pawn d5 is safety
blocked when Black's kingside pawns have good prospects to be advanced. But
maybe the most important factor is that White has no active plan and should
wait when Black begins to act. Many of you know how hard such a task is.} 22...
f5 23. Ree1 Qd6 24. Kh1 Rf8 25. Bf3 Rc7 26. Qg2 h5 {Äèàãðàììà [#]
During next 10 moves opponents maneuver without pawn moves, so nothing serious
happens.} 27. Bd1 Bf6 28. Ba4 Rcf7 29. Qe2 Kg7 30. Rf3 Re7 31. Qg2 Bg5 32. Rff1
Ref7 33. Qe2 Re7 34. Qg2 a6 35. Bc6 {Many chess players can say that Spassky
has improved his bishop but this is not true. From c6 the bishop is unable to
do anything good for the king side. It is a typical example of the bad "good"
bishop. It looks good but in fact, it is terrible.} Ref7 {Äèàãðàììà 
[#]} 36. b4 ({White could not prevent Bd8-c7 idea with} 36. Qe2 $2 {because of}
e4 $1 37. dxe4 {and now} fxe4 $1 ({but not} 37... Qxg3 $2 38. e5 $1 Qxh3+ 39.
Qh2 {and already White is better}) 38. Rxf7+ Rxf7 39. Qg2 (39. Qxe4 {is even
worse} Re7 40. Qb1 Qxg3 41. Rxe7+ Bxe7 $19) 39... e3 $17 {with a clear
advantage.}) 36... Bd8 $1 37. bxc5 bxc5 38. Rb1 Bc7 {[#] Now, e5-e4 is a
serious threat, that is hard to cope with.} 39. Ba4 e4 $1 40. dxe4 $2 ({
White had an interesting idea to sacrifice the pawn in order to reach the
endgame.} 40. Rbe1 $1 exd3 $6 ({an inhuman} 40... Qe5 $1 {with an idea of
e4-e3 was stronger.}) 41. Re6 Qxg3 42. Rf3 $1 Qxg2+ 43. Kxg2 Rf6 $1 (43... d2
44. d6 $1) 44. Rxd3 Bd6 $17 {still better for Black but White got at least
some saving chances.}) 40... fxe4 $1 {Now the attack destroys the position of
the White king.} 41. Rxf7+ Rxf7 42. Bd1 {White covers the f3-square, but Black
pieces easily increase pressure.} e3 43. Bf3 h4 $1 44. Rf1 (44. gxh4 $2 Rxf3
$19) 44... hxg3 {[#] Black is winning.} 45. Qe2 Qe5 46. Kg2 Ba5 47. Rb1 $2 Kh6
$2 ({Black had missed a tactic that would happen a few moves later.} 47... Rxf3
$1 48. Kxf3 (48. Qxf3 e2 $19) 48... Qf5+ $19) 48. Rb3 Bd2 49. Rb6 {
Äèàãðàììà [#]} Rxf3 $1 {Now the combination arose in a more
complicated view.} 50. Re6 (50. Kxf3 Qh5+ $19) (50. Qxf3 e2 $1 51. Qf8+ Kg5 52.
Qd8+ Kh5 $19 {and square h8 is covered by the queen.}) 50... Qxe6 $1 {Without
this move White would be winning.} 51. dxe6 Rf2+ 52. Kxg3 (52. Qxf2 gxf2 53. e7
e2 54. e8=Q f1=Q+ 55. Kg3 e1=Q+ $19) 52... Rxe2 53. e7 Rg2+ $1 {One more move,
that Black had to foresee when he made his 49-th move.} 54. Kxg2 e2 55. e8=Q
e1=Q {White has no a perpetual check.} 56. Qf8+ ({or} 56. Qh8+ Kg5 57. Qd8+ Kh5
58. Qh8+ (58. Qd5+ Kh6) 58... Bh6 $19) 56... Kh5 57. Qxc5+ Bg5 {White resigned.
} 0-1

