{[#]} 18. Bc2 $6 {Judit Polgar decided to bring her bishop to c6 and this
appears a serious positional mistake. It is funny that in the Polgar-Dominguez
game on the move 19 I suggested White to bring the bishop on c6  (the
Hungarian player didn't do this and lost). Now I criticize the analogic
decision. What's the difference between these two cases? First of all, here
the bishop felt fine on the b1-h7 diagonal when the bishop was passive in the
game against Dominguez . Secondly, in this game there is no idea how to
combine something active with the bishop on c6 – it is alone there; in the
game against Dominguez, the bishop had the reasonable hopes to be joined by
other pieces to attack the opponent's queenside. The engine offers many
interesting ideas in this position. I liked the following one more of all.} (
18. fxe5 $1 Nxe5 19. Bb1 Nd3 {The principal continuation; Black wants to take
the bishop on e3.} 20. Ne4 $3 {A nice move that gives White an advantage.} Nxe4
(20... Nxc1 $4 {leads to a checkmate} 21. Nxf6+ gxf6 22. Qg4+ Kh8 23. Qf5 $18)
21. Qxd3 g6 22. Bd4 f5 $2 {Here Black might feel good unless White had the move
} 23. g4 $1 $18) 18... exf4 19. Bxf4 g6 20. Ba4 $6 {Bishop does not change its
path.} ({A back move} 20. Nb1 $5 {would be a good alternative; the knight
moves to b5.}) 20... Bg7 21. Bc6 Rad8 22. Qf3 $2 {The mistake which forces the
exchange of Bf4.} ({The engines insists on} 22. c5 $1 bxc5 23. Nc4 {with a
sufficient compensation.}) (22. Nb1 $5 {still was interesting}) 22... Ne5 23.
Bxe5 Rxe5 {[#] The position on the diagram is better for Black because of
known reasons – Bc6 is not good on its outpost; Black has a pawn majority on
the kingside.} 24. Rce1 Qe7 25. Qg3 Ng4 $1 {Anand prepares the advancing of
the kingside pawns.} 26. Nf3 Rxe1 ({In the rapid game it is practically
impossible to see the move} 26... Ne3 $1 {which forces the knights exchange.}
27. Nxe5 Nxf1 28. Rxf1 Bxe5 $17) 27. Rxe1 Ne5 28. a3 Qc7 29. Nxe5 Bxe5 30. Qf2
Kg7 $17 {[#] Position is close to winning. Black simply advances on the king
side.} 31. b4 axb4 32. axb4 h5 33. Qe3 {Beginning from here the opponents paid
no attention to the c4-c5 move.} Qa7 $6 ({The correct way to prevent c4-c5 was
} 33... Rb8 $1 {followed by Qa7-a2 idea. And if White plays} 34. c5 {Black
wins on h2.} bxc5 35. bxc5 dxc5 36. Qxc5 Bxh2 $19) 34. g3 $2 ({Here} 34. c5 $1
{was possible}) 34... h4 $2 {[#]} ({The move} 34... Bf6 $1 {would prevent
c4-c5 idea.}) 35. gxh4 $2 ({The last time in the game White misses her
counterplay chance.} 35. c5 $1 hxg3 36. cxd6 Bxd6 37. Qd4+ f6 38. Re6 Be5 39.
Rxe5 fxe5 40. Qxe5+ Kg8 41. Qf6 {with good practical chances to save half the
point.}) 35... Rh8 $19 {Now it is over.} 36. Qf2 Bf6 37. Rf1 Qe7 38. Re1 Qd8
39. Re2 Bxh4 40. Qf4 Bg5 41. Qf2 Bf6 42. c5 bxc5 43. bxc5 Qb8 (43... Be5 44.
cxd6 Rxh2+ $19 {was simpler.}) 44. cxd6 Qxd6 {[#] Even with only two pawns
left on the board, Black can develop a decisive attack.} 45. Qe3 Rh5 46. Rf2
Be5 47. Qf3 Qe7 48. Re2 ({White had to sacrifice her pawn by a move} 48. d6 $5
{in order to unblock the bishop.}) 48... Qg5 49. Qf1 Qg3 50. Qf2 Qd3 51. h4
Qh3+ 52. Kg1 Rxh4 {White resigned. Bc6 was an absolutely useless piece.} 0-1

