{Fabiano Caruana showed an example of a technical play in the middlegame with
the opposite-colored bishops against Teimour Radjabov. His opponent couldn't
do much in the position with triple pawns. The opening has just ended. White
is better thanks to the better pawn structure.} 14. Be3 Qg6 15. Qd3 $5 {
Fabiano demonstrated his confidence - even c2xd3 followed by Rac1 would
satisfy him.} (15. Bxc5 $2 {was bad due to} Bh3 16. g3 Rf5 {with a win of the
material.}) 15... Bf5 16. Qc4+ Be6 17. Qe2 ({After} 17. Qxc5 $2 Bd5 {White
can't defend the kingside with a move} 18. f3 {because of} Rxf3) 17... c4 ({
Black could try to defend the pawn by a move} 17... Rf5 $5 {in order not to
block Be6.}) 18. f3 {A demonstration of the important idea. Since White has a
pawn on the f-file, he is able to restrict the opponent's bishop on the long
diagonal.} a6 19. Bd4 Rae8 20. Kh1 Bd5 21. Qd2 Re6 22. Bc3 {[#] Bishop took
the perfect square from where it defends the b2-pawn, attacks the g7-pawn and
can not be pushed away by Black pieces.} h6 23. Rf2 Kh7 24. Raf1 {Not a
compulsory pair of moves from Fabiano, but nothing can change the evaluation -
White has a long-term advantage.} Rf5 25. Re1 {White grabs the e5-square for
the bishop (with a pawn on f7 it would not be possible!).} Rd6 ({Exchange of
the pair of rooks would not solve all problems:} 25... Rxe1+ 26. Qxe1 Rf8 27.
Qe7 (27. Re2 $2 Rxf3 $1) 27... Qf7 28. Re2 Qxe7 29. Rxe7 Rf7 30. Re8 $18) 26.
Be5 Rd7 (26... Rxe5 27. Rxe5 Bxf3 {would not give a sufficient compensation
after} 28. Qc3 $1 $18) 27. Qc3 Qg5 28. Rfe2 Rdf7 29. Re3 {White needed to
defend on f3 to prevent possible tactics on this square.} h5 30. R1e2 Qg6 31.
h3 {White's construction on the kingside is uncrushable, White pieces took
perfect squares, and Stockfish 14 evaluates the position +3. For a human's eye,
it is too much, but it is hard to argue with SF.} Qg5 32. Kh2 {
Äèàãðàììà [#]} h4 $6 {Black made a pseudo-active move that just
creates a weakness.} (32... Rd7 {was more resistible.}) 33. Qd4 $1 {White got
a simple plan - to bring the queen to g4 in order to exchange it and to attack
on h4 after that.} Re7 34. Qg4 $1 Kg8 35. Bc3 $1 {The bishop goes to ... e1!}
Rxe3 36. Rxe3 Kf7 (36... Qxe3 $4 37. Qxg7#) 37. Be1 Qf4+ (37... Qxe3 38. Qxf5+
Kg8 39. Bxh4 {would leave Black without a pawn and any real compensation for
it.}) 38. Qxf4 Rxf4 39. Ra3 {[#] White picks up on a6, but the game goes on
since Black rook goes to attack on c2.} Rd4 40. Rxa6 $2 ({Caruana played
inaccurately at this moment.} 40. c3 $1 Rd1 41. Bxh4 Rd2 42. Kg3 Rxb2 43. Bd8
$18 {was a better exchange. White takes both c7 and a6 and gets 3vs1 on the
kingside + a passed pawn on the a-file. This should be enough for a relatively
easy win.}) 40... g5 $2 ({Black miscalculated that White rook (that is so far
from pawn c2 at the moment) will be able to defend it on time after 40...g5.
The correct move order was} 40... Rd1 $1 41. Bc3 (41. Bxh4 $2 Rd2 {of course
White should not allow the rook entering to the second rank in such way}) (41.
Bb4 {at this moment would not secure a win:} Rc1 42. Ra7 g5 43. Rxc7+ Kg6)
41... g5 42. Ra7 Rc1 43. Rxc7+ Ke6 44. Rg7 Rxc2 {and pawn f3 also falls. White
is better, but is this enough for a win? I am not sure.}) 41. Ra7 Rd1 42. Rxc7+
Ke6 {[#]} (42... Kg6 {loses in such a way:} 43. Bc3 Rc1 44. Rg7+ Kh6 45. Rxg5
$1 Kxg5 46. Bd2+ Kf5 47. Bxc1 c3 48. a4 $1 {(surely, White should save this
passed pawn)} cxb2 49. Bxb2 $18) 43. Bb4 $1 c3 ({Here the point is:} 43... Rc1
44. Re7+ Kf5 45. Re2 {and Black does not take on c2.}) 44. Bxc3 Rc1 45. Rg7
Bxa2 $2 {The final mistake.} ({Black still had drawn chances after} 45... Rxc2
46. Rxg5 Bxf3 47. a4 Bd5 {thanks to pressure on g2 and a bad position of the
White king.}) 46. Rxg5 Rxc2 47. Rg6+ Kd7 48. Rg4 Bd5 49. Kg1 {Now White saves
all three pawns on the kingside.} Rc1+ 50. Kf2 Rc2+ 51. Kf1 Be6 {According to
my database Black resigned after 51...Be6, though this move does not make any
sense.} ({The mainline was} 51... Rc1+ 52. Ke2 Rc2+ 53. Kd3 Rf2 {and now} 54.
Bd4 {pushes the Black rook away from the g2-pawn.} Rf1 55. Rxh4 $18) 1-0

