{Sometimes, the attack in the opposite-colored bishops middlegame can be
directed against just a pawn. The position on the diagram arose from a rare
line of the Rye Lopez. Black can be satisfied with the opening results since
he does not experience any problems - lack of space is compensated by an
exchange of two pairs of minor pieces. The presence of the opposite-colored
bishops on the board so far do not affect badly on the play. So, the only
playable nuance of the position that I have managed to note was a probable
weakness of the d6 pawn in case I play d4-d5 and blow up the queenside. But to
make this true I needed an assist from my opponent.} 17. d5 Bd7 18. b4 $5 {
White cleans up the a7-g1 diagonal (even though there is nothing to attack, it
is a pleasure to have it opened).} cxb4 19. cxb4 Rdc8 20. Rc1 (20. Nb3 {
was not great because of} Rc4) 20... a5 $2 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} ({Black
found himself scared with a possible run of the knight to a5. In fact, there
was not so much danger.} 20... f5 {would hold a balance.}) 21. Rxc8 Bxc8 22. a4
$1 {The exchange of all pawns becomes inevitable and Black should resolve the
problem of the d6 pawn.} Qb7 ({In case of} 22... bxa4 {White would need to
find the way to save the b-pawn.} 23. b5 $1 ({A natural move} 23. Qxa4 $2 {
loses the lion's share of the advantage.} Bd7 24. b5 Qe8 25. Rb1 Rb8 26. Qxa5
Rxb5 27. Rxb5 Bxb5 {The point is that after a move} 28. Bb6 {Black can begin
own attack.} Ng6 $1 29. Bc7 Nf4 $1 {with a sufficient compensation.}) 23... Bd7
24. Qe2 Qe8 25. Rb1 a3 26. b6 $16 {The b6-pawn is very strong.}) ({After} 22...
axb4 $2 23. axb5 $18 {White wins on b4 for free.}) 23. bxa5 Rxa5 24. axb5 Rxb5
{[#] It is time to attack on d6.} 25. Qc1 $6 ({The better path for the queen
was} 25. Qa1 $1 {leaving the c1-square for the rook.} Bd7 26. Nc4 Qb8 27. Rc1
$16 {avoiding the line which might happen on move 27.}) 25... Bd7 26. Nc4 Qb8
27. Qa3 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} Rb1 $2 ({We both missed the following line:} 
27... Rb3 $1 28. Qxd6 {(maybe 28.Qa1 leaves White slightly better chances).}
Rb1 $1 29. Bd2 $8 Rxe1+ 30. Bxe1 Qb1 31. Qb4 Qxe4 $11) 28. Rc1 $1 {The key
move that was my main consideration. The d6-pawn is in big trouble.} Rxc1+ 29.
Bxc1 Qc7 $2 ({Black didn't find the best defending move} 29... Qb5 $1 30. Qc3
$14 {White saves the advantage but the d6-pawn survives.} (30. Nxd6 $2 Qe2 31.
h3 (31. g3 $4 Bh3) 31... Qe1+ 32. Kh2 Qxf2 $11)) 30. Nxd6 Qc2 31. h3 $18 {
White is winning but the end of the game appeared too weak to show it here.
Despite the inaccuracies in my play that were opened in the analysis I hope
you liked the plan which I applied in this game.} 1-0

