{The next game, by mistake, has not been put into my article ‘The King is a
Strong Piece <https://www.modern-chess.com/en/chess-academy/article=1564>.’ 
(Modern Chess Magazine - Issue, 22; Article 6). I can’t miss the second
chance. I believe many of you saw the end of the famous game Short-Timman
where the White king has run from g1 to h6 to deliver the checkmate. It
happened with all major pieces on the board but was relatively simple. The
king's play in this game has amazed me much more. At first look, it is not
even obvious that White plays for a win. The bishop on d7 is pinned and there
is no way to avoid the mass exchanges on the d-file. But one of the heroes of
the last World Cup, Michal Krasenkow has found out that there is a possibility
for the quiet king's walk.} 31. Kh2 $1 {The king goes to f5 to prepare the
queen exchange.} Kg8 32. a4 Kh8 33. f3 Kg8 34. Kh3 $1 Kh8 35. Kg4 $1 Kg8 36.
Kf5 $1 Kf8 {Äèàãðàììà [#] Ok, the king is here, what's next?} 37. f4
$1 ({There was also a possibility to play} 37. Qd5 $6 {right away. But it
would be premature:} Qxd5 38. Rxd5 Bf6 {and now} 39. f4 {is not so effective}
exf4 40. gxf4 Ke7 41. Bc6 ({or} 41. e5 Bxe5 42. Kxe5 Rxd7 43. Rxd7+ Kxd7 44. f5
Ke7 45. Kd5 Kd7 $11) 41... Bb2 {White can play e4-e5, Ke4, but it might not be
enough for a win. Krasenkow prefaces the Qd5-idea.}) 37... exf4 38. gxf4 Kg8 $6
{Black has not recognized the opponent's idea.} ({The king had to be on f8 to
be ready for the possible endgame.} 38... Qa8 $1 {[#] The following line looks
too long but I strongly recommend you to look at this till the end. In my
opinion, the king's job there is magic!} 39. Kg4 $1 {The king races back to g3
to defend the g2-square and to prepare the e4-e5 advancing} (39. Qd5 $6 {
leads to the endgame positions we already saw.} Qxd5+ 40. Rxd5 Bh4 $1 41. e5
Ke7 42. Bc6 Bg3 {White is better but the drawn chances are very high.}) 39...
Qb7 40. Kg3 {Black needs to play} g5 $1 {to stop White's original idea.} (40...
Qa8 $2 {is bad} 41. e5 Kg8 42. Qf5 {followed by e5-e6 with a decisive attack.})
41. hxg6 fxg6 42. e5 Kg7 {[#] Position remains not so easy to play. Black
pieces are passive, but White still has a problem of Bd7. What to do?} 43. Kh2
$3 {White frees the g-file for attack on g6.} ({Stockfish 14 surprisingly
gives almost '+4' in the endgame after} 43. Qd5 $1 Qxd5 44. Rxd5) 43... Kh7 $1
44. Rd2 (44. Rg1 $2 {would fail to} Bg5 $1) (44. f5 Bg5 45. fxg6+ Kg7 {is also
not so clear}) 44... Kg7 ({rook can not leave the d8-square:} 44... Rf8 $2 45.
Rg2 Rg8 46. Be6 Rg7 47. f5 $18) 45. Kg1 $1 {King goes away from Bg5xf4 check,
Rg2 is ready.} ({The engine says that a pendulum movement here also grants the
decisive advantage.} 45. Rg2 g5 46. Rd2 {but it is so nice to bring the king
back to g1 to force Black to look for one more move.}) 45... h5 (45... Kh7 $2
46. Rg2 Bg5 (46... Rg8 47. Be6 Rg7 48. Rh2 $1 $18 {followed by Rxh6.}) 47. e6
$18) 46. Rg2 g5 47. Rd2 $1 g4 48. f5 $18 {[#] A really great job by the king:
Kg1-h2-h3-g4-f5-g4-g3-h2-g1, when all other pieces are left on the same
squares (except of the modest Rd1-d2).}) 39. Qd5 $1 {It is the right moment
for the exchange. The Black king is late to defend the position.} Qxd5+ 40.
Rxd5 {[#] The main Black's problem is the White king's march to b6.} Bf6 ({
Another line is:} 40... Bh4 41. Ke5 Be7 {(it is forced because of Kd6 threat)}
42. Bg4 $1 Bf6+ {Temporarily, the White king is pushed back, but even this
does not help.} 43. Kf5 Kf8 (43... Rxd5+ $2 44. exd5 Kf8 45. d6 $18 {and
nothing can stop the Kf5-e4-d5-c6xb6 maneuver.}) 44. Rxd8+ Bxd8 45. Ke5 Bc7+
46. Kd5 Ke7 47. Kc6 Bd8 {Black defends on b6 but White has zugzwang ideas
which help to win:} 48. e5 Ke8 49. Kb7 Ke7 50. Kc8 Ke8 51. Bd7+ Ke7 52. f5 $18)
41. e5 Bh4 42. e6 $1 fxe6+ 43. Bxe6+ ({White could also take the pawn with the
king:} 43. Kxe6 Rf8 44. Kd6 Rxf4 45. Rf5 $1 Rxf5 (45... Rxc4 $4 46. Be6+) 46.
Bxf5 Kf7 47. Kc7 $18) 43... Kf8 44. Rxd8+ Bxd8 {As we have already seen in the
annotations to the previous moves, the rook exchange does not help Black to
save the game.} 45. Ke4 Ke7 46. Kd5 Kf6 ({Or} 46... Bc7 47. Kc6 Bd8 (47... Bxf4
48. Bh3 $18) 48. f5 Ke8 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} 49. Kb7 $1 {King goes to c8
to put Black in zugzwang.} Kf8 50. Kc8 Ke8 (50... Bf6 51. Kc7 $18) 51. Bd7+ Ke7
52. Bc6 $18) 47. Kd6 Be7+ (47... g6 48. hxg6 Kxg6 49. Kd7 Bf6 50. Kc7 $18) 48.
Kd7 Bf8 49. Bh3 g5 50. hxg6 Kxg6 51. Kc7 {Black resigned. An excellent job by
Michal Krasenkow!} 1-0

