[SourceQuality "2"]

{The battle between two top Ukrainian players was mainly with the advantage of
White but in one moment it could have been radically turned over. I find this
example very instructive to understand how easily the initiative can be lost
and found in the middlegames with the opposite-colored bishops. White has a
defended passed on e5, when Black's "balance" is negative - he has a weak pawn
on d5, that will require a defense (in case if White doubles on the d-file and
brings the bishop to f3). So, White is better. Let's attack the weakness? No!
Areshchenko does not forget about prophylactic thinking. The opponent might be
willing to play b5-b4 creating threats on the queenside. That's why the next
move is required for White.} 22. b4 $1 $14 {Fixes the advantage.} ({In the
Khairullin,I-Fressinet,L (Moscow, 2006) game White played this move after the
previous} 22. Rfd1 Rfd8 23. b4 {which is also fine.}) 22... Rfd8 23. h3 ({
Seemingly, it was more accurate to begin with} 23. Rfd1 Rac8 24. Rd4 $1 $16)
23... Rac8 24. Rfd1 h5 ({From the practical point of view a move} 24... d4 $5 {
looks interesting. But mathematically, this move does not help Black.} 25. Qxc6
Rxc6 26. cxd4 $1 (26. Rxd4 Rxd4 27. cxd4 {is worse because of a prophylactic
move} Rc8 $1 {which prevents axb5 and Ra8.} (27... Bxb4 $2 28. axb5 axb5 29.
Ra8+ Kf7 30. g4 $16 {and White central pawns are very dangerous.}) 28. axb5
axb5 {here White is better after both 29.g4 and 29. d5 but the advantage is
far from the decisive.}) 26... Bxb4 ({there is not an option to block the
d-pawn:} 26... Rd5 $2 27. axb5 axb5 28. g4 $1 {and Be4 will kick the rook off})
27. d5 Rb6 28. axb5 axb5 29. Ra7 Bc5 30. Rc7 $1 $18 {and White gets the
winning position (from the engine's point of view) thanks to more advanced
pawns and more active pieces. But for a human, there are many questions left.})
25. Rd4 {Now White has all-time in the world.} h4 26. a5 {White naturally does
not want to consider b5xa4; moreover, a weakness on a6 can be used later.} Rc7
27. Rad1 Rcd7 {Äèàãðàììà [#]} 28. R1d2 $1 {Areshchenko has a simple
plan – his B comes to f3 and the d5-pawn appears in big trouble. For this
reason, Korobov decided to take a risk on the kingside.} Qe6 29. Qe3 $1 Kg7 30.
Bd1 {After Bf3 White will always have the idea of Qe3-e1-d1 to attack on d5
the fourth time. So, Black pushed forward!} g5 {[#]} 31. Bc2 $1 {As a master
soccer player, the White bishop changes his direction once the defender trusts
that it goes to f3.} (31. fxg5 Qg6 {was exactly what Black expected.}) ({
In case of} 31. Bf3 {Black could defend on g5 by the king.} Kg6) 31... Qg6 32.
Rf2 Rf8 ({White has an instructive exchange operation after} 32... g4 33. hxg4
Qxg4 34. Qh3 $1 {The simplest.} Qxh3+ 35. gxh3 Rf8 36. Rg2+ Kh6 {[#] And now
there is almost a total stalemate for Black pieces. White can bring his king
to e3, then to play Rd4-d1-g1, to put the king on d4 and to pick up all the
opponent's weaknesses.} 37. Kg1 $1 $18) {Despite more than +2. 5 for White
from the engine. In practice, it is far from the whole point in the scoresheet.
} 33. Rd1 $6 {A first inaccuracy.} ({White  miscalculated something after the
forcing move} 33. fxg5 {Black has no  satisfactory defense.} Qxg5 ({after} 
33... Bxg5 {White attacks both weaknesses} 34. Qf3 $18) 34. Rdf4 $18 {with
multiple threats - e5-e6, Qd4 or even Qb6 and then Bxf5.}) 33... gxf4 34. Qxf4
Bg5 35. Qf3 Qe6 {[#]} 36. Bxf5 $2 {Was not the best moment to take this pawn.
Black instantly gets a decent play.} ({Instead White needed to care more about
the initiative.} 36. g3 $1 {The Black king would be unhappy to face the
opening of the g-file.} Bh6 ({Black has no  hope in case of} 36... hxg3 $2 37.
Qxg3 Kh6 38. h4 Bd8 39. Rg1 $18) 37. Rg1 Kh8 38. Qh5 $18 {followed by a
capture on f5.}) 36... Qxe5 37. Qg4 Kh6 $1 {The king bravely defends himself.}
38. Rf3 $2 {[#] A mistake that was left unpunished.} ({After a correct move} 
38. Rdf1 {the position would remain unclear.}) 38... Rdf7 $2 ({After one more
strong move Black could take the advantage. That's the main trick of the
middlegames with the opposite-colored bishops – this is so easy to lose the
initiative.} 38... Rg7 $1 {The point is that the Black king is already out of
danger. But we can't say the same about the White king. Black aims to bring
his bishop to the b8-h2 diagonal. Here White has a beautiful move} 39. Bg6 $1 {
but this does not help to secure the position.} Be7 $1 (39... Rxf3 $4 40. Qh5#)
(39... Bf4 $2 40. Rdf1 Rxg6 41. Qxh4+ Kg7 42. Rxf4 Rxf4 43. Rxf4 {with better
chances for White thanks to a more safe king's location.} (43. Qxf4 $2 Qxf4 44.
Rxf4 Rg3 $17 {loses the important c3-pawn.})) 40. Rxf8 Bxf8 41. Qf5 Bd6 $19 {
and the queen side pawns become easy prey for the black bishop.}) 39. Rdf1 {
A g2-g3 threat puts Black on the edge of the abyss.} Rf6 $2 {Korobov could not
find a proper defending way.} ({The engine suggests} 39... Qg7 $1 {with an
idea to meet} 40. g3 {by a move} Be7 {but such moves rarely get into the
human's consideration.}) 40. g3 $1 $18 {The attack is unstoppable.} hxg3 41. h4
Bd2 42. Rxg3 Rd6 {Qe5 defends on g7.} (42... Rxf5 $4 43. Qg6#) 43. Rg2 Be3 44.
Rf3 Bc1 45. Rg1 Bd2 {[#]} 46. Be6 $1 {A double attack – Qg6 and Rxf8 are
hanging. It is over. Worth mentioning that this move was already possible on
the previous move , but Areshchenko decided to prevent even a tiny counterplay
(Qe1).} Qxe6 (46... Rxf3 47. Qg6#) 47. Qg7+ Kh5 48. Qxf8 Qe4 49. Rg2 Rg6 50.
Qf5+ {Black resigned. It is a good example of how the winds can change (moves
38 and 39) in the middlegames with the opposite-colored bishops.} 1-0

[Event "Croatia Grand Chess Tour"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "2019.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Nepomniachtchi, Ian"]
[Black "Carlsen, Magnus"]
[Result "0-1"]
[WhiteElo "2775"]
[BlackElo "2875"]
[Annotator "GM Valeriy Aveskulov"]
[SetUp "1"]
[FEN "1r3r1k/4qpb1/3p3p/1ppBp1pP/4PnP1/3P1P2/QPPB1K2/R4R2 b - - 0 25"]
[PlyCount "21"]
[EventDate "2019.??.??"]
[Source "Mark Crowther"]

{To end the article I would like to show the game played by the World Champion
and the Challenger (far before their match). In this one, Magnus felt the
right moment to rush forward. In the position on the diagram White looks solid.
Control of the only open file and all light squares should guarantee him
safety. But the World Champion has managed to blow everything up just in a few
moves.} 25... c4 $1 {The first explosion!} 26. Bxf4 ({After} 26. dxc4 bxc4 27.
Bxc4 {[#] Black had a variety of possible continuations.} d5 $5 (27... f5 $5
28. exf5 (28. gxf5 $4 {loses to} g4 $1 $19 {followed by Qh4}) 28... Rfc8 $44 {
with d6-d5 or e5-e4 ideas.} (28... d5 {is less obvious because White sets a
strong blockade on the light squares.} 29. Bxf4 (29. Bxd5 $4 Qc5+ 30. Kg3 Nxd5
$19) 29... gxf4 30. Bxd5 Rfc8 31. Be4 Qh4+ 32. Ke2 {and now only move} Rb4 $44
{with an idea to take on e4 gives Black a decent compensation.})) (27... Rfc8
$5 {is a tricky practical decision. Black improves one more piece before a new
explosion. White needs to calculate both d6-d5 and f7-f5.}) 28. Bxd5 (28. exd5
$2 f5 $1 29. gxf5 g4 $1 30. fxg4 Qh4+ $19) 28... f5 $1 29. Kg3 $1 {The king
feels himself safe here.} Nxd5 30. Qxd5 Rfd8 31. Qa5 fxg4 32. fxg4 Rxb2 $13)
26... exf4 27. Rad1 {[#] Nepomniachtchi decided to keep the queen side lines
closed and to open the Bg7 instead.} f5 $1 {A new explosion that sets
difficult practical tasks before the opponent. Now the only move can hold a
balance.} 28. gxf5 $4 {Loses on spot.} (28. Kg2 $4 fxg4 29. fxg4 f3+ 30. Rxf3
Rxf3 31. Kxf3 Rf8+ 32. Kg2 Qf6 $19) (28. d4 $2 fxg4 29. fxg4 f3 {followed by
Rf4 -+}) (28. exf5 $1 {was the correct move. Black can't damage much having
the only opened file "e". The position would remain complicated in all lines.}
Qe3+ $1 (28... Bd4+ 29. Kg2 Qe2+ 30. Kh3 $1 (30. Kh1 {is less accurate because
after} Bf2 {(with an idea of Bg3 and Qh2) White can't pretend for more than a
draw. [#]} 31. b4 $1 {A nice geometric motif. At first, it looks so, that
Black should win after a move Bf2-g3 but White uses all parts of the board to
get the winning position there.} (31. Qa5 b4 32. Rxf2 Qxf2 33. Qc7 $11 {
both kings are too weak to avoid the perpetual checks.}) 31... Rfe8 $1 (31...
Bg3 $4 32. Qa1+ Kh7 33. Qa7+ Rb7 $1 {A nice answer but White should not take
the rook.} (33... Kh8 34. Qd4+ Kh7 35. Qg1 $18 {White is a pawn up without any
compensation.}) 34. Qg1 $18 (34. Qxb7+ $4 Kh8 {leads to a checkmate.})) 32.
Qa1+ Re5 33. Rxf2 Qxf2 34. dxc4 Kh7 35. Rf1 Qh4+ 36. Kg1 Qg3+ $11) 30... Rfe8
$1 $13 {with a complicated position.} (30... cxd3 $2 {is bad due to} 31. c3 Bf6
32. Qb1 $16) ({a try to play for a checkmate fails because of Rh1 move.} 30...
Bf2 $2 31. Qa6 Bg3 32. Rh1 Rfd8 33. dxc4 $18)) 29. Kg2 Qe2+ 30. Kh3 cxd3 31.
cxd3 Qxb2 $11) 28... g4 $1 $19 {White can't defend against all threats.} 29. d4
(29. Rh1 Bd4+ 30. Ke2 gxf3+ 31. Kxf3 Qg5 $19) (29. fxg4 Bd4+ 30. Ke2 Qh4 31.
Rde1 (31. Kd2 Be3+ 32. Kc3 b4+ 33. Kxc4 {[#]} b3 $1 $19 {A nice touch! Kb3 is
prevented; the rest is simple.}) 31... Qxg4+ 32. Kd2 Qg2+ 33. Kc1 cxd3 34. cxd3
Rfc8+ 35. Kb1 Rc2 $19) 29... Qh4+ 30. Ke2 Qh2+ 31. Rf2 gxf3+ 32. Kxf3 (32. Ke1
Qg1+ 33. Rf1 Qe3#) 32... Qg3+ 33. Ke2 Qe3+ 34. Kf1 Bxd4 35. Rxd4 Qxd4 {White
resigned because nothing can help him to handle with an including of the Black
rook (by means of Rg8).} 0-1

